# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: astrophysics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] An **accretion disk** is a structure (often a circumstellar disk) formed by diffuse material in orbital motion around a massive central body.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The central body is most frequently a star.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Friction, uneven irradiance, magnetohydrodynamic effects, and other forces induce instabilities causing orbiting material in the disk to spiral inward toward the central body.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Gravitational and frictional forces compress and raise the temperature of the material, causing the emission of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The frequency range of that radiation depends on the central object's mass.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Accretion disks of young stars and protostars radiate in the infrared; those around neutron stars and black holes in the X-ray part of the spectrum.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The study of oscillation modes in accretion disks is referred to as **diskoseismology**.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] These jets are invoked by astronomers to do everything from getting rid of angular momentum in a forming star to reionizing the universe (in active galactic nuclei), but their origin is still not well understood.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Accretion disks are a ubiquitous phenomenon in astrophysics; active galactic nuclei, protoplanetary disks, and gamma ray bursts all involve accretion disks.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] These disks very often give rise to astrophysical jets coming from the vicinity of the central object.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Jets are an efficient way for the star-disk system to shed angular momentum without losing too much mass.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The most prominent accretion disks are those of active galactic nuclei and of quasars, which are thought to be massive black holes at the center of galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] As matter enters the accretion disc, it follows a trajectory called a tendex line, which describes an inward spiral.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] This is because particles rub and bounce against each other in a turbulent flow, causing frictional heating which radiates energy away, reducing the particles' angular momentum, allowing the particle to drift inward, driving the inward spiral.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The loss of angular momentum manifests as a reduction in velocity; at a slower velocity, the particle must adopt a lower orbit.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] As the particle falls to this lower orbit, a portion of its gravitational potential energy is converted to increased velocity and the particle gains speed.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Thus, the particle has lost energy even though it is now travelling faster than before; however, it has lost angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The large luminosity of quasars is believed to be a result of gas being accreted by supermassive black holes.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Elliptical accretion disks formed at tidal disruption of stars can be typical in galactic nuclei and quasars.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The accretion process can convert about 10 percent to over 40 percent of the mass of an object into energy as compared to around 0.7 percent for nuclear fusion processes.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In close binary systems the more massive primary component evolves faster and has already become a white dwarf, a neutron star, or a black hole, when the less massive companion reaches the giant state and exceeds its Roche lobe.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] A gas flow then develops from the companion star to the primary.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Angular momentum conservation prevents a straight flow from one star to the other and an accretion disk forms instead.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Accretion disks surrounding T Tauri stars or Herbig stars are called protoplanetary disks because they are thought to be the progenitors of planetary systems.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The accreted gas in this case comes from the molecular cloud out of which the star has formed rather than a companion star.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] This animation (2013) of supercomputer data takes the viewer to the inner zone of the accretion disk of a stellar-mass black hole.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In the 1940s, Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker developed model for the formation of stars from accreting gas.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In order to agree with observations, those models had to invoke a yet unknown mechanism for angular momentum redistribution.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] If matter is to fall inward it must lose not only gravitational energy but also lose angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Since the total angular momentum of the disk is conserved, the angular momentum loss of the mass falling into the center has to be compensated by an angular momentum gain of the mass far from the center.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In other words, angular momentum should be *transported* outward for matter to accrete.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] where $\Omega$ represents the angular velocity of a fluid element and R its distance to the rotation center, an accretion disk is expected to be a laminar flow.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] This prevents the existence of a hydrodynamic mechanism for angular momentum transport.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] On one hand, it was clear that viscous stresses would eventually cause the matter toward the center to heat up and radiate away some of its gravitational energy.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] On the other hand, viscosity itself was not enough to explain the transport of angular momentum to the exterior parts of the disk.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Turbulence-enhanced viscosity was the mechanism thought to be responsible for such angular-momentum redistribution, although the origin of the turbulence itself was not well understood.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The conventional $\alpha$ -model (discussed below) introduces an adjustable parameter $\alpha$ describing the effective increase of viscosity due to turbulent eddies within the disk.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In 1991, with the rediscovery of the magnetorotational instability (MRI), S.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Hawley established that a weakly magnetized disk accreting around a heavy, compact central object would be highly unstable, providing a direct mechanism for angular-momentum redistribution.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Shakura and Sunyaev (1973) proposed turbulence in the gas as the source of an increased viscosity.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] By using the equation of hydrostatic equilibrium, combined with conservation of angular momentum and assuming that the disk is thin, the equations of disk structure may be solved in terms of the $\alpha$ parameter.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Many of the observables depend only weakly on $\alpha$ , so this theory is predictive even though it has a free parameter.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The Shakura–Sunyaev α-disk model is both thermally and viscously unstable.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] An alternative model, known as the $\beta$ -disk, which is stable in both senses assumes that the viscosity is proportional to the gas pressure $\nu \propto \alpha p_{\mathrm {gas} }$ .
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In the standard Shakura–Sunyaev model, viscosity is assumed to be proportional to the total pressure $p_{\mathrm {tot} }=p_{\mathrm {rad} }+p_{\mathrm {gas} }=\rho c_{\rm {s}}^{2}$ since $\nu =\alpha c_{\rm {s}}H=\alpha c_{s}^{2}/\Omega =\alpha p_{\mathrm {tot} }/(\rho \Omega )$ .
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The Shakura–Sunyaev model assumes that the disk is in local thermal equilibrium, and can radiate its heat efficiently.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In this case, the disk radiates away the viscous heat, cools, and becomes geometrically thin.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] However, this assumption may break down.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In the radiatively inefficient case, the disk may "puff up" into a torus or some other three-dimensional solution like an Advection Dominated Accretion Flow (ADAF).
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The ADAF solutions usually require that the accretion rate is smaller than a few percent of the Eddington limit.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Another extreme is the case of Saturn's rings, where the disk is so gas-poor that its angular momentum transport is dominated by solid body collisions and disk-moon gravitational interactions.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The model is in agreement with recent astrophysical measurements using gravitational lensing.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Balbus and Hawley (1991) proposed a mechanism which involves magnetic fields to generate the angular momentum transport.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] A simple system displaying this mechanism is a gas disk in the presence of a weak axial magnetic field.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Two radially neighboring fluid elements will behave as two mass points connected by a massless spring, the spring tension playing the role of the magnetic tension.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In a Keplerian disk the inner fluid element would be orbiting more rapidly than the outer, causing the spring to stretch.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The inner fluid element is then forced by the spring to slow down, reduce correspondingly its angular momentum causing it to move to a lower orbit.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The outer fluid element being pulled forward will speed up, increasing its angular momentum and move to a larger radius orbit.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The spring tension will increase as the two fluid elements move further apart and the process runs away.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Most astrophysical disks do not meet this criterion and are therefore prone to this magnetorotational instability.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The magnetic fields present in astrophysical objects (required for the instability to occur) are believed to be generated via dynamo action.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Accretion disks are usually assumed to be threaded by the external magnetic fields present in the interstellar medium.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] These fields are typically weak (about few micro-Gauss), but they can get anchored to the matter in the disk, because of its high electrical conductivity, and carried inward toward the central star.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] This process can concentrate the magnetic flux around the centre of the disk giving rise to very strong magnetic fields.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Formation of powerful astrophysical jets along the rotation axis of accretion disks requires a large scale poloidal magnetic field in the inner regions of the disk.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Such magnetic fields may be advected inward from the interstellar medium or generated by a magnetic dynamo within the disk.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Magnetic fields strengths at least of order 100 Gauss seem necessary for the magneto-centrifugal mechanism to launch powerful jets.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] There are problems, however, in carrying external magnetic flux inward toward the central star of the disk.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] High electric conductivity dictates that the magnetic field is frozen into the matter which is being accreted onto the central object with a slow velocity.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] However, the plasma is not a perfect electric conductor, so there is always some degree of dissipation.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The magnetic field diffuses away faster than the rate at which it is being carried inward by accretion of matter.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] A simple solution is assuming a viscosity much larger than the magnetic diffusivity in the disk.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] However, numerical simulations and theoretical models show that the viscosity and magnetic diffusivity have almost the same order of magnitude in magneto-rotationally turbulent disks.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Some other factors may possibly affect the advection/diffusion rate: reduced turbulent magnetic diffusion on the surface layers; reduction of the Shakura–Sunyaev viscosity by magnetic fields; and the generation of large scale fields by small scale MHD turbulence –a large scale dynamo.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] In fact, a combination of different mechanisms might be responsible for efficiently carrying the external field inward toward the central parts of the disk where the jet is launched.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Magnetic buoyancy, turbulent pumping and turbulent diamagnetism exemplify such physical phenomena invoked to explain such efficient concentration of external fields.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] When the accretion rate is sub-Eddington and the opacity very high, the standard thin accretion disk is formed.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] It is geometrically thin in the vertical direction (has a disk-like shape), and is made of a relatively cold gas, with a negligible radiation pressure.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The gas goes down on very tight spirals, resembling almost circular, almost free (Keplerian) orbits.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Thin disks are relatively luminous and they have thermal electromagnetic spectra, i.e. not much different from that of a sum of black bodies.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Radiative cooling is very efficient in thin disks.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The classic 1974 work by Shakura and Sunyaev on thin accretion disks is one of the most often quoted papers in modern astrophysics.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Thin disks were independently worked out by Lynden-Bell, Pringle, and Rees.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Pringle contributed in the past thirty years many key results to accretion disk theory, and wrote the classic 1981 review that for many years was the main source of information about accretion disks, and is still very useful today.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Due to light bending, the disk appears distorted but is nowhere hidden by the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] When the accretion rate is sub-Eddington and the opacity very low, an ADAF (advection dominated accretion flow) is formed.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] This type of accretion disk was predicted in 1977 by Ichimaru.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Although Ichimaru's paper was largely ignored, some elements of the ADAF model were present in the influential 1982 ion-tori paper by Rees, Phinney, Begelman, and Blandford.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] ADAFs started to be intensely studied by many authors only after their rediscovery in the early 1990s by Popham and Narayan in numerical models of accretion disk boundary layers.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Self-similar solutions for advection-dominated accretion were found by Narayan and Yi, and independently by Abramowicz, Chen, Kato, Lasota (who coined the name ADAF), and Regev.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Most important contributions to astrophysical applications of ADAFs have been made by Narayan and his collaborators.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] ADAFs are cooled by advection (heat captured in matter) rather than by radiation.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] They are very radiatively inefficient, geometrically extended, similar in shape to a sphere (or a "corona") rather than a disk, and very hot (close to the virial temperature).
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Because of their low efficiency, ADAFs are much less luminous than the Shakura–Sunyaev thin disks.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] ADAFs emit a power-law, non-thermal radiation, often with a strong Compton component.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] happen in many accretion disks, with their periods appearing to scale as the inverse of the mass of the central object.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Why are there sometimes overtones, and why do these appear at different frequency ratios in different objects?
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The theory of highly super-Eddington black hole accretion, *M*≫*M*Edd, was developed in the 1980s by Abramowicz, Jaroszynski, Paczyński, Sikora, and others in terms of "Polish doughnuts" (the name was coined by Rees).
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Polish doughnuts are low viscosity, optically thick, radiation pressure supported accretion disks cooled by advection.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Polish doughnuts resemble in shape a fat torus (a doughnut) with two narrow funnels along the rotation axis.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The funnels collimate the radiation into beams with highly super-Eddington luminosities.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] Slim disks (name coined by Kolakowska) have only moderate super-Eddington accretion rates, *M*≥*M*Edd, rather disk-like shapes, and almost thermal spectra.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] They are cooled by advection, and are radiatively ineffective.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] They were introduced by Abramowicz, Lasota, Czerny, and Szuszkiewicz in 1988.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] The opposite of an accretion disk is an decretion disk where instead of material accreting from a disk on to a central object, material is excreted from the center outward onto the disk.
[src:astrophysics/accretion-disk] They are formed from matter ejected from a star, and are often assosicated with Be stars.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Among the subjects studied are the Sun (solar physics), other stars, galaxies, extrasolar planets, the interstellar medium, and the cosmic microwave background.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Emissions from these objects are examined across all parts of the electromagnetic spectrum, and the properties examined include luminosity, density, temperature, and chemical composition.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In practice, modern astronomical research often involves substantial work in the realms of theoretical and observational physics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Some areas of study for astrophysicists include the properties of dark matter, dark energy, black holes, and other celestial bodies; and the origin and ultimate fate of the universe.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Astronomy is an ancient science, long separated from the study of terrestrial physics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Consequently, it was held that the celestial region was made of a fundamentally different kind of matter from that found in the terrestrial sphere; either Fire as maintained by Plato, or Aether as maintained by Aristotle.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] During the 17th century, natural philosophers such as Galileo, Descartes, and Newton began to maintain that the celestial and terrestrial regions were made of similar kinds of material and were subject to the same natural laws.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Their challenge was that the tools had not yet been invented with which to prove these assertions.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] For much of the nineteenth century, astronomical research was focused on the routine work of measuring the positions and computing the motions of astronomical objects.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] A new astronomy, soon to be called astrophysics, began to emerge when William Hyde Wollaston and Joseph von Fraunhofer independently discovered that, when decomposing the light from the Sun, a multitude of dark lines (regions where there was less or no light) were observed in the spectrum.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] By 1860 the physicist, Gustav Kirchhoff, and the chemist, Robert Bunsen, had demonstrated that the dark lines in the solar spectrum corresponded to bright lines in the spectra of known gases, specific lines corresponding to unique chemical elements.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Kirchhoff deduced that the dark lines in the solar spectrum are caused by absorption by chemical elements in the Solar atmosphere.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In this way it was proved that the chemical elements found in the Sun and stars were also found on Earth.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Among those who extended the study of solar and stellar spectra was Norman Lockyer, who in 1868 detected radiant, as well as dark lines in solar spectra.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Working with chemist Edward Frankland to investigate the spectra of elements at various temperatures and pressures, he could not associate a yellow line in the solar spectrum with any known elements.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] He thus claimed the line represented a new element, which was called helium, after the Greek Helios, the Sun personified.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Pickering undertook an ambitious program of stellar spectral classification at Harvard College Observatory, in which a team of woman computers, notably Williamina Fleming, Antonia Maury, and Annie Jump Cannon, classified the spectra recorded on photographic plates.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] By 1890, a catalog of over 10,000 stars had been prepared that grouped them into thirteen spectral types.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Following Pickering's vision, by 1924 Cannon expanded the catalog to nine volumes and over a quarter of a million stars, developing the Harvard Classification Scheme which was accepted for worldwide use in 1922.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In 1895, George Ellery Hale and James E.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Keeler, along with a group of ten associate editors from Europe and the United States, established *The Astrophysical Journal: An International Review of Spectroscopy and Astronomical Physics*.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Around 1920, following the discovery of the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram still used as the basis for classifying stars and their evolution, Arthur Eddington anticipated the discovery and mechanism of nuclear fusion processes in stars, in his paper *The Internal Constitution of the Stars*.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] At that time, the source of stellar energy was a complete mystery; Eddington correctly speculated that the source was fusion of hydrogen into helium, liberating enormous energy according to Einstein's equation *E = mc2*.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] This was a particularly remarkable development since at that time fusion and thermonuclear energy, and even that stars are largely composed of hydrogen (see metallicity), had not yet been discovered.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In 1925 Cecilia Helena Payne (later Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin) wrote an influential doctoral dissertation at Radcliffe College, in which she applied Saha's ionization theory to stellar atmospheres to relate the spectral classes to the temperature of stars.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Most significantly, she discovered that hydrogen and helium were the principal components of stars, not the composition of Earth.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Despite Eddington's suggestion, discovery was so unexpected that her dissertation readers (including Russell) convinced her to modify the conclusion before publication.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] However, later research confirmed her discovery.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] By the end of the 20th century, studies of astronomical spectra had expanded to cover wavelengths extending from radio waves through optical, x-ray, and gamma wavelengths.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In the 21st century, it further expanded to include observations based on gravitational waves.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Observational astronomy is a division of the astronomical science that is concerned with recording and interpreting data, in contrast with theoretical astrophysics, which is mainly concerned with finding out the measurable implications of physical models.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] It is the practice of observing celestial objects by using telescopes and other astronomical apparatus.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Most astrophysical observations are made using the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Other than electromagnetic radiation, few things may be observed from the Earth that originate from great distances.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] A few gravitational wave observatories have been constructed, but gravitational waves are extremely difficult to detect.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Neutrino observatories have also been built, primarily to study the Sun.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Cosmic rays consisting of very high-energy particles can be observed hitting the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Observations can also vary in their time scale.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Most optical observations take minutes to hours, so phenomena that change faster than this cannot readily be observed.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] However, historical data on some objects is available, spanning centuries or millennia.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] On the other hand, radio observations may look at events on a millisecond timescale (millisecond pulsars) or combine years of data (pulsar deceleration studies).
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] The information obtained from these different timescales is very different.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] The study of the Sun has a special place in observational astrophysics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Due to the tremendous distance of all other stars, the Sun can be observed in a kind of detail unparalleled by any other star.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Understanding the Sun serves as a guide to understanding of other stars.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] The topic of how stars change, or stellar evolution, is often modeled by placing the varieties of star types in their respective positions on the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, which can be viewed as representing the state of a stellar object, from birth to destruction.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Theoretical astrophysicists use a wide variety of tools which include analytical models (for example, polytropes to approximate the behaviors of a star) and computational numerical simulations.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Analytical models of a process are generally better for giving insight into the heart of what is going on.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Numerical models can reveal the existence of phenomena and effects that would otherwise not be seen.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Theorists in astrophysics endeavor to create theoretical models and figure out the observational consequences of those models.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] This helps allow observers to look for data that can refute a model or help in choosing between several alternate or conflicting models.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Theorists also try to generate or modify models to take into account new data.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In the case of an inconsistency, the general tendency is to try to make minimal modifications to the model to fit the data.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In some cases, a large amount of inconsistent data over time may lead to total abandonment of a model.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Relativistic astrophysics serves as a tool to gauge the properties of large-scale structures for which gravitation plays a significant role in physical phenomena investigated and as the basis for black hole physics and the study of gravitational waves.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Some widely accepted and studied theories and models in astrophysics, now included in the Lambda-CDM model, are the Big Bang, cosmic inflation, dark matter, dark energy and fundamental theories of physics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Historically, when astronomy was limited by astrometry and observational astronomy, the field of celestial mechanics (CM) was referred to as **theoretical astronomy**.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Hipparchus made foundational contributions to the field through the development of a numerical observation geometry system.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] However, Isaac Newton is considered the founder of the field through his development of calculus and the law of universal gravitation and the majority of the field is based on Kepler's laws of planetary motion.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Theodor von Oppolzer expanded the work on CM and geodetic astronomy within the field at the University of Vienna in the late 19th century.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Soon after the discovery of Cepheid variable stars, theorists shifted from CM and geodesy to the development of theoretical mechanisms for the composition and internal physics of stars.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] The field then expanded into other areas such as cosmology, plasma physics, and hydrodynamics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In Sweden in the early 1930s, Svein Rosseland funded the Institute of Theoretical Astrophysics, which opened in 1934, to advance what he said had developed into a separate science.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In 1966, a small group of astronomers led by Fred Hoyle established the Institute of Theoretical Astronomy at the University of Cambridge to allow theorists to focus entirely on computational research without any teaching responsibilities.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Despite that theoretical astronomy and astrophysics were being used interchangeably throughout the 20th century, university courses titled "theoretical astronomy" exclusively taught CM.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In 1985, the University of Virginia, which had been home to the largest refractor in the world and used primarily by the United States Naval Observatory, opened the Virginia Institute of Theoretical Astronomy to host research in both theoretical astronomy and astrophysics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] Modern theoretical astronomy is the use of mathematical and computational tools to model and predict the motions of astronomical objects.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In astronomy curriculum, theoretical astronomy is used in conjunction with observational techniques, and unpaired, the field would not be considered a science.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] It is foundational in the field of planetary science.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] The roots of astrophysics can be found in the seventeenth century emergence of a unified physics, in which the same laws applied to the celestial and terrestrial realms.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] There were scientists who were qualified in both physics and astronomy who laid the firm foundation for the current science of astrophysics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] In modern times, students continue to be drawn to astrophysics due to its popularization by the Royal Astronomical Society and notable educators such as prominent professors Lawrence Krauss, Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar, Stephen Hawking, Hubert Reeves, Carl Sagan and Patrick Moore.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] The efforts of the early, late, and present scientists continue to attract young people to study the history and science of astrophysics.
[src:astrophysics/astrophysics] The television sitcom show *The Big Bang Theory* popularized the field of astrophysics with the general public, and featured some well known scientists like Stephen Hawking and Neil deGrasse Tyson.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] effect produces two enlarged but distorted views of the Cloud.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A **black hole** is an astronomical body so compact that its gravity prevents anything, including light, from escaping.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity, which describes gravitation as the curvature of spacetime, predicts that any sufficiently compact mass will form a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The boundary of no escape is called the event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In general relativity, crossing a black hole's event horizon traps an object inside but produces no locally detectable change.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] General relativity also predicts that every black hole should have a central singularity, where the curvature of spacetime is infinite.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Objects whose gravitational fields are too strong for light to escape were first considered in the 18th century.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1916, the first solution of general relativity that would characterise a black hole was found.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] By the late 1950s, this solution began to be interpreted physically as a region of space from which nothing can escape.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Black holes were long considered a mathematical curiosity; it was not until the 1960s that theoretical work showed they were a generic prediction of general relativity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The first widely accepted black hole was Cygnus X-1, identified by several researchers independently in 1971.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Black holes typically form when very massive stars collapse at the end of their life cycle.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] After a black hole has formed, it can grow by absorbing mass from its surroundings.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Supermassive black holes of millions of solar masses may form by absorbing stars and merging with other black holes, or via direct collapse of gas clouds.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] There is consensus that supermassive black holes exist in the centres of most galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Quantum field theory in curved spacetime predicts that event horizons emit Hawking radiation, with its rate of emission being inversely proportional to its mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This causes the black hole to lose mass very slowly, provided it is not accreting matter.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, even the smallest class of black holes observed, stellar black holes, are gaining mass from the cosmic microwave background faster than they are losing mass via Hawking radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The presence of a black hole can be inferred through its interaction with matter and electromagnetic radiation such as visible light.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Matter falling toward a black hole can form an accretion disk of infalling plasma, heated by friction and emitting light.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In extreme cases, this creates a quasar, some of the brightest objects in the universe.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Merging black holes can be detected by the gravitational waves they emit.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] If stars are orbiting a black hole, their motions can be used to determine the black hole's mass and location.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In this way, astronomers have identified numerous stellar black hole candidates in binary systems and established that the radio source known as Sagittarius A*, at the core of the Milky Way galaxy, contains a supermassive black hole of about 4.3 million solar masses.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The idea of a body so massive that even light could not escape was first proposed in the late 18th century by English astronomer and clergyman John Michell and independently by French scientist Pierre-Simon Laplace.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Both scholars proposed very large stars in contrast to the modern concept of an extremely dense object.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Michell's idea, in a short part of a letter published in 1784, calculated that a star with the same density but 500 times the radius of the sun would not let any emitted light escape; the surface escape velocity would exceed the speed of light.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Michell correctly hypothesized that such non-radiating bodies might be detectable through their gravitational effects on nearby visible bodies.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1796, while speculating on the origin of the Solar System in his book *Exposition du Système du Monde*, Laplace made a qualitative suggestion that a star could be invisible if it were sufficiently large.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Franz Xaver von Zach asked Laplace for a mathematical analysis, which Laplace provided and published in von Zach's journal *Allgemeine Geographische Ephemeriden*.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1905, Albert Einstein showed that the laws of electromagnetism are identical for observers travelling at different velocities relative to each other.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The laws of mechanics had already been shown to be invariant in this way.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, the theory of gravitation was yet to be included.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1907, Einstein published a paper proposing his equivalence principle, the hypothesis that inertial mass and gravitational mass have a common cause.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Using the principle, Einstein predicted the redshift and the lensing effect of gravity on light; his prediction of gravitational lensing was one-half of the value that the full theory of general relativity would predict.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] By 1915, Einstein refined these ideas into his general theory of relativity, which explained how matter affects spacetime, which in turn affects the motion of other matter.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This formed the basis for black hole physics.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Only a few months after Einstein published the field equations describing general relativity, astrophysicist Karl Schwarzschild set out to apply the idea to stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] He assumed spherical symmetry with no spin and found a solution to Einstein's equations.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A few months after Schwarzschild, Johannes Droste, a student of Hendrik Lorentz, independently gave the same solution.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] At a certain radius from the centre of the mass, the Schwarzschild solution became singular, meaning that some of the terms in the Einstein equations became infinite.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The nature of this radius, which later became known as the Schwarzschild radius, was not understood at the time.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Many physicists of the early 20th century were sceptical of the existence of black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In a 1926 popular science book, Arthur Eddington critiqued the idea of a star with mass compressed to its Schwarzschild radius as a flaw in the then-poorly-understood theory of general relativity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1939, Einstein used his theory of general relativity in an attempt to prove that black holes were impossible.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] His work relied on increasing pressure or increasing centrifugal force balancing the force of gravity so that the object would not collapse beyond its Schwarzschild radius.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] He missed the possibility that implosion would drive the system below this critical value.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] By the 1920s, astronomers had classified a number of white dwarf stars as too cool and dense to be explained by the gradual cooling of ordinary stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1926, Ralph Fowler showed that these stars are not like main-sequence stars, where thermal pressure balances gravity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Instead, a type of quantum-mechanical pressure balances gravity at these temperatures and densities.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1931, Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar studied the new state of matter that results from this balance, called electron-degenerate matter, discovering that it is stable below a certain limiting mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] By 1934 he showed that this explained the catalogue of white dwarf stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] When Chandrasekhar announced his results, Eddington pointed out that stars above this limit would radiate until they were sufficiently dense to prevent light from exiting, a conclusion he considered absurd.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Eddington and, later, Lev Landau argued that some yet unknown mechanism would stop the collapse.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In the 1930s, Fritz Zwicky and Walter Baade studied stellar novae, focusing on exceptionally bright ones they called supernovae.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Zwicky promoted the idea that supernovae produced stars with the density of atomic nuclei—neutron stars—but this idea was largely ignored at the time.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1939, based on Chandrasekhar's reasoning, but working within general relativity rather than Newtonian gravity, J.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Robert Oppenheimer and George Volkoff predicted that neutron stars below a certain mass limit, later called the Tolman–Oppenheimer–Volkoff limit, would be stable due to neutron degeneracy pressure.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Above that limit, they reasoned that either their model would not apply or that gravitational contraction would not stop.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] John Archibald Wheeler and two of his students resolved questions about the model behind the Tolman–Oppenheimer–Volkoff (TOV) limit.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1965, Harrison and Wheeler developed the equations of state relating density to pressure for cold matter all the way through electron degeneracy and neutron degeneracy.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Masami Wakano and Wheeler then used the equations to compute the equilibrium curve for stars, relating mass to circumference.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] They found no additional features that would invalidate the TOV limit.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This meant that the only thing that could prevent black holes from forming was a dynamic process ejecting sufficient mass from a star as it cooled.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The modern concept of black holes was formulated by Robert Oppenheimer and his student Hartland Snyder in 1939.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In the paper, Oppenheimer and Snyder solved Einstein's equations of general relativity for an idealised imploding star, in a model later called the Oppenheimer–Snyder model, then described the results from far outside the star.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The implosion starts as one might expect: the star material rapidly collapses inward.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, as the density of the star increases, gravitational time dilation increases and the collapse, viewed from afar, seems to slow down further and further until the star reaches its Schwarzschild radius, where it appears frozen in time.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1958, David Finkelstein identified the Schwarzschild surface as an event horizon, calling it "a perfect unidirectional membrane: causal influences can cross it in only one direction".
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This means that events that occur inside the black hole cannot affect events that occur outside the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Finkelstein created a new reference frame to include the point of view of infalling observers.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Finkelstein's new frame of reference allowed events at the surface of an imploding star to be related to events far away.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] By 1962 the two points of view were reconciled, convincing many sceptics that implosion into a black hole made physical sense.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The era from the mid-1960s to the mid-1970s was the "golden age of black hole research", when general relativity and black holes became mainstream subjects of research.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In this period, solutions to the equations of general relativity under various different physical constraints were discovered.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1963, Roy Kerr found the exact solution for a rotating black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Two years later, Ezra Newman found the axisymmetric solution for a black hole that is both rotating and electrically charged.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In the late 1960s and early 1970s scientists from research groups formed by Yakov Zeldovich, John Archibald Wheeler and Dennis W.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Sciama discovered a series of important mathematical properties of black hole models dubbed "a black hole has no hair" by Wheeler.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The first hints came from work by Vitaly Ginzburg who studied a series of increasing compact stars threaded with intense magnetic fields.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] He discovered that the fields get trapped on the black hole surface.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1967, Werner Israel showed that any non-spinning, uncharged collapsing star gives a spherically symmetric black hole: any asymmetry must somehow vanish.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Price found that the asymmetry was converted into gravitational waves.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] It took another 15 years and many physicists to produce a body of work that became known as the no-hair theorem, which states that a stationary black hole is completely described by the three parameters of the Kerr–Newman metric: mass, angular momentum, and electric charge.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This view was held in particular by Vladimir Belinski, Isaak Khalatnikov, and Evgeny Lifshitz, who tried to prove that no singularities appear in generic solutions, although they would later reverse their positions.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, in 1965, Roger Penrose proved that general relativity predicts that singularities appear in all black holes, although this may not still hold when quantum mechanics is taken into account.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Astronomical observations also made great strides during this era.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1967, Antony Hewish and Jocelyn Bell Burnell discovered pulsars and by 1969, these were shown to be rapidly rotating neutron stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Until that time, neutron stars, like black holes, were regarded as just theoretical curiosities, but the discovery of pulsars showed their physical relevance and spurred a further interest in all types of compact objects that might be formed by gravitational collapse.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, experimental evidence confirming a black hole was very difficult to obtain and ultimately required efforts from many astronomers.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] X-ray telescope observations by Riccardo Giacconi's team in 1971 showed that Cygnus X-1 emitted x-rays in rapid, sporadic fashion consistent with a compact source.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This became the first candidate black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Optical spectroscopy and detailed astrophysical models for Cygnus X-1 were consistent with a binary system of a massive star and compact star generating x-rays as gas from the massive but ordinary star was sucked into its invisible compact companion.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] (In 2011, the masses of these stars was estimated to be 14.1±1.0 *M*☉ for the black hole and 19.2±1.9 *M*☉ for the optical stellar companion.) By 1974 the object was widely considered to be a black hole, but 100% confidence for Cygnus X-1 may not be possible.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Work by James Bardeen, Carter, and Hawking in the early 1970s led to the formulation of black hole thermodynamics.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] These laws describe the behaviour of a black hole in a manner analogous to the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Jacob Bekenstein strengthened this analogy with the properties of mass, surface area, and surface gravity for a black hole related to the thermodynamical concepts of energy, entropy, and temperature respectively.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The analogy was completed when Hawking, in 1974, showed that quantum field theory implies that black holes should radiate like a black body with a temperature proportional to the surface gravity of the black hole, predicting the effect now known as Hawking radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] While Cygnus X-1, a stellar-mass black hole, was generally accepted by the scientific community as a black hole by the end of 1973, it would be decades before a supermassive black hole would gain the same broad recognition.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The idea that such objects might exist began with models suggesting that powerful quasars or active galactic nuclei in the centre of galaxies were powered by accreting supermassive black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] When the Hubble Space Telescope launched in the 1990s, optical studies of the centre of galaxy Messier 87 showed it must have a large concentration of mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The two candidates for this mass were a black hole and a dense cluster of stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1995, interferometric microwave spectra from the Very Long Baseline Array observed H 2O masers as they orbited the centre of NGC 4258, a galaxy with a similar central mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The orbital parameters ruled out dense stellar clusters as an explanation for galactic nuclei, making supermassive black holes the only plausible explanation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 1999, David Merritt proposed the M–sigma relation, which related the dispersion of the velocity of matter in the centre bulge of a galaxy to the mass of the supermassive black hole at its core.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Subsequent studies confirmed this correlation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In late 2015, the LIGO Scientific Collaboration and Virgo Collaboration made the first direct detection of gravitational waves, named GW150914, representing the first observation of a black hole merger.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] At the time of the merger, the black holes were approximately 1.4 billion light-years away from Earth and had masses roughly 30 and 35 times that of the Sun.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 2017, Rainer Weiss, Kip Thorne, and Barry Barish, who had spearheaded the project, were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics for their work.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Since the initial discovery in 2015, hundreds more gravitational waves have been observed.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] On 10 April 2019, the first direct image of a black hole and its vicinity was published, following observations made by the Event Horizon Telescope (EHT) of the supermassive black hole in Messier 87's galactic centre.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 2022, the Event Horizon Telescope collaboration released an image of the black hole in the center of the Milky Way galaxy, Sagittarius A*; the data had been collected in 2017.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In 2020, the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded for work on black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Andrea Ghez and Reinhard Genzel shared one-half for their discovery that Sagittarius A* is a supermassive black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Penrose received the other half for his work showing that the mathematics of general relativity requires the formation of black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Cosmologists lamented that Hawking's extensive theoretical work on black holes would not be honoured since he had died in 2018.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, the term was used by others around that time.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Science writer Marcia Bartusiak traces the term *black hole* to physicist Robert H.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Dicke, who in the early 1960s reportedly compared the phenomenon to the Black Hole of Calcutta, notorious as a prison where people entered but never left alive.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The term was used in print by *Life* and *Science News* magazines in 1963, and by science journalist Ann Ewing in her article "'Black Holes' in Space", dated 18 January 1964, which was a report on a meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science held in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A black hole is generally defined as a region of spacetime from which no information-carrying signals or objects can escape.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, verifying an object as a black hole by this definition would require waiting for an infinite time and at an infinite distance from the black hole to verify that nothing has escaped, and thus cannot be used to identify a physical black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] There are several other definitions that can be used to describe or identify black holes, leading to a variety of ways to study them.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Astronomical observations measure the mass of objects and gravitational collapse theories predict that a compact object with a mass larger than three solar masses can only be a black hole: this limit has become the observational definition.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A black hole may also be defined as a reservoir of information or a region where space is falling inwards faster than the speed of light.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The no-hair theorem establishes that, once it achieves a stable condition after formation, a black hole has only three independent physical properties: mass, electric charge, and angular momentum; the black hole is otherwise featureless.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Any two black holes that share the same values for these properties, or parameters, are indistinguishable from one another.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A related *no hair conjecture* proposes that dynamic gravitational collapse always results in an object characterized with only these three properties.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The conjecture is currently an unsolved problem.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The no hair theorem also makes idealized assumptions in addition to equilibrium that may not apply to astrophysical objects.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The simplest equilibrium black hole model with only mass but neither electric charge nor angular momentum is called a *Schwarzschild black hole*.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Non-rotating charged black holes are described by the Reissner–Nordström metric, while the Kerr metric describes a non-charged rotating black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The most general stationary black hole solution known is the Kerr–Newman metric, which describes a black hole with both charge and angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The simplest static black holes have mass but neither electric charge nor angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Contrary to the popular notion of a black hole "sucking in everything" in its surroundings, from far away, the external gravitational field of a black hole is identical to that of any other body of the same mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] While a black hole can theoretically have any positive mass, its charge and angular momentum are limited by its mass, with this limit being greater for more massive black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Black holes with the maximum possible combination of charge and spin satisfying this inequality are called extremal black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Adding a low-mass object with a lot of charge or angular momentum to an extremal black hole would create a so-called naked singularity, a singularity outside of a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Because these singularities make the universe inherently unpredictable, many physicists believe they could not exist.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The weak cosmic censorship hypothesis, proposed by Penrose, rules out the formation of such singularities, when they are created through the gravitational collapse of realistic matter.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This hypothesis remains an important area of study because has not yet been proven and it relates to many aspects of general relativity and quantum gravity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The total mass of a nearby black hole can be estimated by analysing the motion of the stars or gas surrounding it.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The mass of distant supermassive black holes can be inferred from Doppler broadening of spectral lines emitted by rapidly orbiting gas, a technique called reverberation mapping.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] All black holes spin, often fast—One stellar black hole, GRS 1915+105, has been estimated to spin at over 1,000 revolutions per second.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The Milky Way's central black hole Sagittarius A* rotates at about 90% of the maximum possible rate.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The spin rate can be inferred from measurements of atomic spectral lines in the X-ray range.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] As gas near the black hole plunges inward, high energy X-ray emission from electron-positron pairs illuminates the gas further out, appearing red-shifted due to relativistic effects.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Depending on the spin of the black hole, this plunge happens at different radii from the hole, with different degrees of redshift.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Astronomers can use the gap between the x-ray emission of the outer disk and the redshifted emission from plunging material to determine the spin of the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A newer way to estimate spin is based on the temperature of gases accreting onto the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The method requires an independent measurement of the black hole mass and inclination angle of the accretion disk followed by computer modelling.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Gravitational waves from coalescing binary black holes can also provide the spin of both progenitor black holes and the merged hole, but such events are rare.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A spinning black hole has angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The Kerr metric is the solution of Einstein's field equations for a rotating black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In addition to the Schwarzschild radius, $r_{\textrm {S}}$ , it includes a rotational parameter, $a={\frac {J}{M}}={\frac {2J}{r_{\textrm {S}}}},$ where J is the black hole angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] An extremal black hole has $|J|=M^{2}$ , corresponding to $a=1$ .
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The supermassive black hole in the centre of the Messier 87 (M87) galaxy appears to have rotational parameter of 0.90±0.05, very close to the maximum theoretical value.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Black holes are believed to have an approximately neutral charge.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For example, Michal Zajaček, Arman Tursunov, Andreas Eckart, and Silke Britzen found the electric charge of Sagittarius A* to be at least ten orders of magnitude below the theoretical maximum.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] If a black hole were to become charged, particles with an opposite sign of charge would be pulled in by the extra electromagnetic force, while particles with the same sign of charge would be repelled, neutralising the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This effect operates even more rapidly if the black hole is also spinning.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A spinning black hole in a magnetic field creates an electric field which would interact with charged particles.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Since black holes have so few measurable intrinsic properties, techniques for measuring charge are of interest to astrophysics even if the values may be very small.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The charge Q for a nonspinning black hole is bounded by $Q\leq {\sqrt {4\pi \epsilon _{0}G}}M,$ where G is the gravitational constant and M is the black hole's mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Black holes are classified by the theory of their formation and by their mass (expressed in terms of *M*☉, the mass of the Sun), but these criteria are intertwined.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Stellar black holes are formed by stellar collapse.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The minimum mass of a black hole formed by stellar gravitational collapse is governed by the maximum mass of a neutron star and is believed to be 2-4 *M*☉.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Hypothetical primordial black holes, believed to have formed soon after the Big Bang, could be far smaller, with masses as little as 10−5 grams at formation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] These very small black holes are sometimes called micro black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Stellar black holes can have a wide range of masses.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Estimates of their maximum mass at formation vary, but generally range from 10-100 *M*☉, with higher estimates for black holes progenated by low-metallicity stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Stellar black holes can gain mass via accretion of nearby matter, often from a companion object such as a star or by merger with another black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A small number of candidate black holes with masses in the range 102-104 *M*☉ have been reported.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] These are larger than stellar black holes but smaller than supermassive black holes, are rarer than either extreme, and are called intermediate-mass black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Physicists have speculated that such black holes may form from collisions in globular and star clusters or at the centre of low-mass galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] They may also form as the result of mergers of smaller black holes, with several gravitational wave measurements consistent with merged black holes within 110–350 *M*☉.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The black holes with the largest masses are called supermassive black holes, with masses more than 106 *M*☉.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] These black holes are believed to exist at the centres of almost every large galaxy, including the Milky Way.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Some scientists have proposed a subcategory of even larger black holes, called ultramassive black holes, with masses greater than 109-1010 *M*☉.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Theoretical models predict that the accretion disc that feeds black holes will be unstable once a black hole reaches 50×109–100×109 *M*☉, setting a rough upper limit to black hole mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] While black holes are conceptually invisible sinks of all matter and light, in astronomical settings, their enormous gravity alters the motion of surrounding objects and pulls nearby gas inwards at near-light speed, making the area around black holes the brightest objects in the universe.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Some black holes have relativistic jets—thin streams of plasma travelling away from the black hole at more than 90% of the speed of light.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] A small fraction of the matter falling towards the black hole gets accelerated away along the hole rotation axis.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] These jets can extend as far as millions of light-years from the black hole itself.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, they are typically observed around spinning black holes with strongly-magnetized accretion disks.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Relativistic jets were more common in the early universe, when galaxies and their corresponding supermassive black holes were rapidly gaining mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] All black holes with jets also have an accretion disk, but the jets are usually brighter than the disk.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] *Quasars,* typically found in other galaxies, are believed to be supermassive black holes with jets; *microquasars* are believed to be stellar-mass objects with jets, typically observed in the Milky Way.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The jets can be powered by either the accretion disk or the rotating black hole spin.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] While many details of the jets have been studied, no complete model has emerged.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] One method proposed to fuel these jets is the Blandford-Znajek process, which suggests that the dragging of magnetic field lines by a black hole's rotation could launch jets of matter into space.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The Penrose process, which involves extraction of a black hole's rotational energy, has also been proposed as a potential mechanism of jet propulsion.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] There is evidence that jets at all scales, from microquasars to gamma ray bursts may be produced by a single mechanism.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Due to conservation of angular momentum, gas falling into the gravitational well created by a massive object will typically form a disk-like structure around the object.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The temperature of these disks can range from thousands to millions of kelvins, and temperatures differ throughout a single accretion disk.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Accretion disks radiate across the entire electromagnetic spectrum, depending on the disk's turbulence and magnetisation and the black hole's mass and angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Accretion disks can be defined as geometrically thin or geometrically thick.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Geometrically thin disks are mostly confined to the black hole's equatorial plane and have a well-defined edge at the innermost stable circular orbit (ISCO), while geometrically thick disks are supported by internal pressure and temperature and can extend inside the ISCO.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Disks with high rates of electron scattering and absorption, appearing bright and opaque, are called *optically thick*; *optically thin* disks are more translucent and produce fainter images when viewed from afar.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Accretion disks of black holes accreting beyond the Eddington limit are often referred to as *polish donuts* due to their thick, toroidal shape that resembles that of a donut.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Quasar accretion disks are expected to have a "blue spectral shape", meaning that the flux per frequency $F_{\nu }$ is proportional to $\nu ^{1/3}$ ; this was not originally observed due to emission from dust surrounding the objects.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The disk for a stellar black hole, on the other hand, would likely look orange, yellow, or red, with its inner regions being the brightest.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Accretion disk colours may also be altered by the Doppler effect, with the part of the disk travelling towards an observer appearing bluer and brighter and the part of the disk travelling away from the observer appearing redder and dimmer.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In Newtonian gravity, test particles can stably orbit at arbitrary distances from a central object.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In general relativity, however, there exists a smallest possible radius for which a massive particle can orbit stably.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Any infinitesimal inward perturbations to this orbit will lead to the particle spiralling into the black hole, and any outward perturbations will, depending on the energy, cause the particle to spiral in, move to a stable orbit further from the black hole, or escape to infinity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This orbit is called the **innermost stable circular orbit**, or ISCO.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For spinning black holes, the ISCO is moved inwards for particles orbiting in the same direction that the black hole is spinning (prograde) and outwards for particles orbiting in the opposite direction (retrograde).
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For example, the ISCO for a particle orbiting retrograde can be as far out as about $4.5r_{\text{s}}$ , while the ISCO for a particle orbiting prograde can be as close as at the event horizon itself.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The radius of this orbit changes slightly based on particle spin.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For charged black holes, the ISCO moves inwards.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The photon sphere is a spherical boundary for which photons moving on tangents to that sphere are bent completely around the black hole, possibly orbiting multiple times.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For Schwarzschild black holes, the photon sphere has a radius 1.5 times the Schwarzschild radius.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] While light can still escape from the photon sphere, any light that crosses the photon sphere on an inbound trajectory will be captured by the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Therefore, any light that reaches an outside observer from the photon sphere must have been emitted by objects between the photon sphere and the event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Light emitted towards the photon sphere may also curve around the black hole and return to the emitter.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For a rotating, uncharged black hole, the radius of the photon sphere depends on the spin parameter and whether the photon is orbiting prograde or retrograde.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For a photon orbiting prograde, the photon sphere will be 0.5-1.5 Schwarzschild radii from the centre of the black hole, while for a photon orbiting retrograde, the photon sphere will be between 3-4 Schwarzschild radii from the centre of the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The exact locations of the photon spheres depend on the magnitude of the black hole's rotation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For a charged, nonrotating black hole, there will only be one photon sphere, and the radius of the photon sphere will decrease for increasing black hole charge.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For non-extremal, charged, rotating black holes, there will always be two photon spheres, with the exact radii depending on the parameters of the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] When viewed from a great distance, the photon sphere creates an observable **black hole shadow,** a dark silhouette of the black hole against the background stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Images such as those taken by the Event Horizon Telescope show the black hole shadow, not the event horizon itself.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Since no light emerges from within the black hole, this shadow is the limit for possible observations.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The shadow of colliding black holes should have characteristic warped shapes, allowing scientists to detect black holes that are about to merge.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Near a rotating black hole, spacetime rotates similar to a vortex.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The rotating spacetime will drag any matter and light into rotation around the spinning black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This effect of general relativity, called frame dragging, gets stronger closer to the spinning mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The region of spacetime in which it is impossible to stay still is called the ergosphere.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The ergosphere of a black hole is a volume bounded by the black hole's event horizon and the *ergosurface* or *stationary limit surface*, which coincides with the event horizon at the poles but bulges out from it around the equator.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Matter and radiation can escape from the ergosphere.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Through the Penrose process, objects can emerge from the ergosphere with more energy than they entered with.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The extra energy is taken from the rotational energy of the black hole, slowing down the rotation of the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The observable region of spacetime around a black hole closest to its event horizon is called the plunging region.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In this area it is no longer possible for free falling matter to follow circular orbits or stop a final descent into the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Instead, it will rapidly plunge toward the black hole at close to the speed of light, growing increasingly hot and producing a characteristic, detectable thermal emission.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, light and radiation emitted from this region can still escape from the black hole's gravitational pull.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The average density of a 108 *M*☉ black hole is comparable to that of water.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Far away from the black hole, a particle can move in any direction, as illustrated by the set of arrows.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] It is restricted only by the speed of light.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Closer to the black hole, spacetime starts to deform.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] There are more paths going towards the black hole than paths moving away.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Inside of the event horizon, all paths bring the particle closer to the centre of the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] It is no longer possible for the particle to escape.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] diagram; in other coordinates the light cones are not tilted in this way.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The defining feature of a black hole is the existence of an event horizon, a boundary in spacetime through which matter and light can pass only inward towards the centre of the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Nothing, not even light, can escape from inside the event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The event horizon is referred to as such because if an event occurs within the boundary, information from that event cannot reach or affect an outside observer, making it impossible to determine whether such an event occurred.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For non-rotating black holes, the geometry of the event horizon is precisely spherical, while for rotating black holes, the event horizon is oblate.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] To a distant observer, a clock near a black hole would appear to tick more slowly than one further from the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This effect, known as gravitational time dilation, would also cause an object falling into a black hole to appear to slow as it approached the event horizon, never quite reaching the horizon from the perspective of an outside observer.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] All processes on this object would appear to slow down, and any light emitted by the object to appear redder and dimmer, an effect known as gravitational redshift.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] An object falling from half of a Schwarzschild radius above the event horizon would fade away until it could no longer be seen, disappearing from view within one hundredth of a second for an 8 *M*☉ black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] It would also appear to flatten onto the black hole, joining all other material that had ever fallen into the hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] On the other hand, an observer falling into a black hole would not notice any of these effects as they cross the event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Their own clocks appear to them to tick normally, and they cross the event horizon after a finite time without noting any singular behaviour.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In general relativity, it is impossible to determine the location of the event horizon from local observations, due to Einstein's equivalence principle.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Black holes that are rotating and/or charged have an inner horizon, often called the Cauchy horizon, inside of the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The inner horizon is divided up into two segments: an ingoing section and an outgoing section.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] At the ingoing section of the Cauchy horizon, radiation and matter that fall into the black hole would build up at the horizon, causing the curvature of spacetime to go to infinity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This would cause an observer falling in to experience tidal forces.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This phenomenon is often called mass inflation, since it is associated with a parameter dictating the black hole's internal mass growing exponentially, and the buildup of tidal forces is called the mass-inflation singularity or Cauchy horizon singularity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Some physicists have argued that in realistic black holes, accretion and Hawking radiation would stop mass inflation from occurring.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] At the outgoing section of the inner horizon, infalling radiation would backscatter off of the black hole's spacetime curvature and travel outward, building up at the outgoing Cauchy horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This would cause an infalling observer to experience a gravitational shock wave and tidal forces as the spacetime curvature at the horizon grew to infinity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This buildup of tidal forces is called the shock singularity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In the Penrose-Hawking singularity theorem, both of these singularities are weak, meaning that an object crossing them would only be deformed a finite amount by tidal forces, even though the spacetime curvature would still be infinite at the singularity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] This is as opposed to a strong singularity, where an object hitting the singularity would be stretched and squeezed by an infinite amount.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] They are also null singularities, meaning that a photon could travel parallel to them without ever being intercepted.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Ignoring quantum effects, every black hole has a singularity inside, points where the curvature of spacetime becomes infinite, and geodesics terminate within a finite proper time.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For a non-rotating black hole, this region takes the shape of a single point; for a rotating black hole it is smeared out to form a ring singularity that lies in the plane of rotation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] In both cases, the singular region has zero volume.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] All of the mass of the black hole ends up in the singularity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Since the singularity has nonzero mass in an infinitely small space, it can be thought of as having infinite density.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Observers falling into a Schwarzschild black hole (i.e., non-rotating and not charged) cannot avoid being carried into the singularity once they cross the event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] As they fall further into the black hole, they will be torn apart by the growing tidal forces in a process sometimes referred to as spaghettification or the *noodle effect*.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Eventually, they will reach the singularity and be crushed into an infinitely small point.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] However, any perturbations, such as those caused by matter or radiation falling in, would cause space to oscillate chaotically near the singularity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Any matter falling in would experience intense tidal forces rapidly changing in direction, all while being compressed into an increasingly small volume.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] Alternative forms of general relativity, including addition of some quantum effects, can lead to *regular*, or *nonsingular*, black holes without singularities.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] For example, the fuzzball model, based on string theory, states that black holes are actually made up of quantum microstates and need not have a singularity or an event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p01] The theory of loop quantum gravity proposes that the curvature and density at the centre of a black hole is large, but not infinite.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black holes are formed by gravitational collapse of massive stars, either by direct collapse or during a supernova explosion in a process called *fallback*.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black holes can result from the merger of two neutron stars or a neutron star and a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Other more speculative mechanisms include primordial black holes created from density fluctuations in the early universe, the collapse of dark stars, a hypothetical object powered by annihilation of dark matter, or from hypothetical self-interacting dark matter.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Gravitational collapse occurs when an object's internal pressure is insufficient to resist the object's own gravity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] At the end of a star's life, it will run out of hydrogen to fuse, and will start fusing more and more massive elements, until it gets to iron.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Since the fusion of elements heavier than iron would require more energy than it would release, nuclear fusion ceases.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] If the iron core of the star is too massive, the star will no longer be able to support itself and will undergo gravitational collapse.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The mass of a black hole formed via a supernova has a lower bound: if the progenitor star is too small, the collapse may be stopped by the degeneracy pressure of the star's constituents, allowing the condensation of matter into an exotic denser state.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Degeneracy pressure occurs from the Pauli exclusion principle: particles will resist being in the same place as each other.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Progenitor stars with masses less than about 8 *M*☉ will become white dwarfs, where the degeneracy pressure of electrons balances gravity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] For more massive progenitor stars, the force of gravity overcomes electron degeneracy pressure and the star compresses until neutron degeneracy pressure resists gravity, forming a neutron star.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] If the star is even more massive, neutron degeneracy pressure will not be able to resist the force of gravity and the star will collapse into a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] While most of the energy released during gravitational collapse is emitted very quickly, an outside observer does not actually see the end of this process.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Even though the collapse takes a finite amount of time from the reference frame of infalling matter, a distant observer would see the infalling material slow and halt just above the event horizon, due to gravitational time dilation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Light from the collapsing material takes longer and longer to reach the observer, with the delay growing to infinity as the emitting material reaches the event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Thus the external observer never sees the formation of the event horizon; instead, the collapsing material seems to become dimmer and increasingly red-shifted, eventually fading away.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Observations of quasars from less than a billion years after the Big Bang has led to investigations of other ways to form black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The accretion process to build supermassive black holes has a limiting rate of mass accumulation and a billion years is not enough time to reach quasar status.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] One suggestion is direct collapse of nearly pure hydrogen gas (low metalicity) clouds characteristic of the young universe, forming a supermassive star which collapses into a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] It has been suggested that seed black holes with typical masses of ~105 *M*☉ could have formed in this way which then could grow to ~109 *M*☉.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However, the very large amount of gas required for direct collapse is not typically stable against fragmentation which would form multiple stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Thus another approach suggests massive star formation followed by collisions that seed massive black holes which ultimately merge to create a quasar.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A neutron star in a common envelope with a regular star can accrete sufficient material to collapse to a black hole or two neutron stars can merge.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] These avenues for the formation of black holes are considered relatively rare.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In the early universe, fluctuations of spacetime may have formed areas that were denser than their surroundings.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Rapid early expansion of the universe may have allowed these areas to collapse, forming primordial black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Various models predict the creation of primordial black holes ranging from a Planck mass (~2.2×10−8 kg) to hundreds of thousands of solar masses.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Primordial black holes with masses less than 1012 kg would have evaporated by now due to Hawking radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Despite the early universe being extremely dense, it did not re-collapse into a black hole during the Big Bang, since the universe was expanding rapidly and did not have the gravitational differential necessary for black hole formation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Models for the gravitational collapse of objects of relatively constant size, such as stars, do not necessarily apply in the same way to rapidly expanding space such as the Big Bang.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In principle, black holes could be formed in high-energy particle collisions that achieve sufficient density, although no such events have been detected.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] These hypothetical micro black holes, which could form from the collision of cosmic rays and Earth's atmosphere or in particle accelerators like the Large Hadron Collider, would not be able to aggregate additional mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Instead, they would evaporate in about 10−25 seconds, posing no threat to the Earth.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] After a black hole forms, it may change through phenomena such as mergers, accretion of matter, and evaporation via Hawking radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black holes can merge with other objects such as stars or other black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This is thought to have been important, especially in the early growth of supermassive black holes, which could have formed from the aggregation of many smaller objects.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The process has also been proposed as the origin of some intermediate-mass black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Mergers of supermassive black holes may take a long time: As a binary of supermassive black holes approach each other, most nearby stars are slingshotted away, leaving little for the black holes to gravitationally interact with that would allow them to get closer to each other.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This phenomenon has been called the final parsec problem, as the distance at which this happens is usually around one parsec.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] When a black hole accretes matter, the gas in the inner accretion disk orbits at very high speeds because of its proximity to the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This fast-moving gas experiences friction against the slower-moving gas in the outer disk, transferring angular momentum to the outer disk.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The loss of angular momentum forces the gas in the inner disk to orbit closer to the black hole, and its gravitational potential energy is converted into thermal energy.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This heats the inner disk to temperatures at which it emits vast amounts of electromagnetic radiation (mainly X-rays), which is detectable by telescopes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] By the time the matter of the disk reaches the ISCO, between 5.7% and 42% of its mass will have been converted to energy, depending on the black hole's spin.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] About 90% of this energy is released within 20 black hole radii.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In many cases, accretion disks are accompanied by relativistic jets that are emitted along the black hole's poles, which carry away much of the energy.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Many of the universe's most energetic phenomena have been attributed to the accretion of matter on black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Active galactic nuclei and quasars are powered by accretion onto supermassive black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] X-ray binaries are generally accepted to be binary systems in which one of the two objects is a compact object accreting matter from its companion.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Ultraluminous X-ray sources may be the accretion disks of intermediate-mass black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] At a certain rate of accretion, the outward radiation pressure will become as strong as the inward gravitational force, and the black hole should, in theory, be unable to accrete any faster.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This limit is called the Eddington limit.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Realistically, many black holes accrete beyond this rate due to their non-spherical geometry or instabilities in the accretion disk.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Accretion beyond the limit is called super-Eddington accretion and may have been commonplace in the early universe.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Stars have been observed to get torn apart by tidal forces in the immediate vicinity of supermassive black holes in galaxy nuclei, in what is known as a tidal disruption event (TDE).
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Some of the material from the disrupted star forms an accretion disk around the black hole, which emits observable electromagnetic radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The correlation between the masses of supermassive black holes in the centres of galaxies with the velocity dispersion and mass of stars in their host bulges suggests that the formation of galaxies and the formation of their central black holes are related.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black hole winds from rapid accretion, particularly when the galaxy itself is still accreting matter, can compress gas nearby, accelerating star formation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However, if the winds become too strong, the black hole may blow nearly all of the gas out of the galaxy, quenching star formation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black hole jets may also energise nearby cavities of plasma and eject low-entropy gas from out of the galactic core, causing gas in galactic centres to be hotter than expected.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] If Hawking's theory of black hole radiation is correct, then black holes are expected to shrink and evaporate over time as they lose mass by the emission of photons and other particles.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The temperature of this thermal spectrum (Hawking temperature) is proportional to the surface gravity of the black hole, which is inversely proportional to the mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Hence, large black holes emit less radiation than small black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A stellar black hole of 1 *M*☉ has a Hawking temperature of 62 nanokelvins.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This is far less than the 2.7 K temperature of the cosmic microwave background radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Stellar-mass or larger black holes receive more mass from the cosmic microwave background than they emit through Hawking radiation and thus will grow instead of shrinking.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] To have a Hawking temperature larger than 2.7 K (and be able to evaporate), a black hole would need a mass less than the Moon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Such a black hole would have a diameter of less than a tenth of a millimetre.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The Hawking radiation for an astrophysical black hole is predicted to be very weak and would thus be exceedingly difficult to detect from Earth.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A possible exception is the microsecond-long burst of gamma rays emitted in the last stage of the evaporation of primordial black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Extensive searches for such radiation have proven unsuccessful and provide upper limits on the possibility of existence of low mass primordial black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] When based in general relativity, the constraints on a black hole's properties are called the laws of black hole mechanics.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] For a black hole that is not still forming or accreting matter, the zeroth law of black hole mechanics states the black hole's surface gravity is constant across the event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The first law relates changes in the black hole's surface area, angular momentum, and charge to changes in its energy.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The second law says the surface area of a black hole never decreases on its own.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Finally, the third law says that the surface gravity of a black hole is never zero.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] These laws are mathematical analogues of the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] They are not equivalent, however, because, according to general relativity without quantum mechanics, a black hole can never emit radiation, and thus its temperature must always be zero.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Quantum mechanics predicts that a black hole will continuously emit thermal Hawking radiation, and therefore must always have a nonzero temperature.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] It also predicts that all black holes have entropy which scales with their surface area.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] When quantum mechanics is accounted for, the laws of black hole mechanics become equivalent to the classical laws of thermodynamics.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However, these conclusions are derived without a complete theory of quantum gravity, although many potential theories do predict black holes having entropy and temperature.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Thus, the true quantum nature of black hole thermodynamics continues to be debated.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Millions of black holes derived from stellar collapse are expected to exist in the Milky Way.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Even a dwarf galaxy like Draco should have hundreds.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] By nature, black holes do not themselves emit any electromagnetic radiation other than the hypothetical, typically extremely weak Hawking radiation, so astrophysicists searching for black holes must rely on indirect observations.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The defining characteristic of a black hole is its event horizon.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The horizon itself cannot be imaged, so all other possible explanations for these indirect observations must be considered and eliminated before concluding that a black hole has been observed.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The Event Horizon Telescope (EHT) is a global system of radio telescopes capable of directly observing a black hole shadow.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The angular resolution of a telescope is based on its aperture and the wavelengths it is observing.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Because the angular diameters of Sagittarius A* and Messier 87* in the sky are very small, a single telescope would need to be about the size of the Earth to clearly distinguish their horizons using radio wavelengths.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] By combining data from several different radio telescopes around the world, the Event Horizon Telescope creates an effective aperture the diameter size of the Earth.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The EHT team used imaging algorithms to compute the most probable image from the data in its observations of Sagittarius A* and M87*.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Gravitational-wave interferometry can be used to detect merging black holes and other compact objects.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In this method, a laser beam is split, sent down two long arms of a tunnel, then reflected at the far end of the tunnels to reconverge at the intersection of the arms, precisely cancelling each other.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However, when a gravitational wave passes, it warps spacetime, changing the relative lengths of the arms themselves.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Since each laser beam is now travelling a slightly different distance, they do not cancel out and produce a recognisable signal.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Analysis of the signal can give scientists information about what caused the gravitational waves.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Since gravitational waves are very weak, gravitational-wave observatories such as LIGO must have arms several kilometres long and carefully control for noise from Earth to be able to detect these gravitational waves.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Since the first measurements in 2016, multiple gravitational waves from black holes have been detected and analysed.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A satellite based gravitational wave instrument, LISA, is under construction with launch planned for approximately 2035.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The mission will consist of three spacecraft flying in a triangular formation with 2.5 million km arm lengths to detect low-frequency gravitational waves from sources such as merging supermassive black holes and compact binary systems.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The proper motions of stars near the centre of the Milky Way provide strong observational evidence that these stars are orbiting a supermassive black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Astronomers have tracked the motions of over 100 stars orbiting an invisible object coincident with the radio source Sagittarius A*.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] One of the stars—called S2—completed a full orbit.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] By fitting the motions of stars to Keplerian orbits, the astronomers were able to infer that the invisible object assumed to be Sagittarius A* must have a mass of 4.3×106 *M*☉, with a radius of less than 0.002 light-years.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This upper limit radius is larger than the Schwarzschild radius for the estimated mass, so the combination does not prove Sagittarius A* is a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Nevertheless, these observations strongly suggest that the central object is a supermassive black hole as there are no other plausible scenarios for confining so much invisible mass into such a small volume.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Additionally, luminosity data from this object implies it must possess an event horizon, a defining feature of black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] By tracking the motion of the centre it has been shown that the central object is motionless at the centre of the galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The Event Horizon Telescope image of Sagittarius A*, released in 2022, provided further confirmation that it is indeed a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] X-ray binaries are binary systems that emit significant amounts of X-ray radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] These X-ray emissions result when a compact object accretes matter from an ordinary star.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The presence of an ordinary star in such a system provides an opportunity for studying the central object and to determine if it might be a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] By measuring the orbital period of the binary, the distance to the binary from Earth, and the mass of the companion star, scientists can estimate the mass of the compact object.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The Tolman-Oppenheimer-Volkoff limit (TOV limit) dictates the largest mass a nonrotating neutron star can be, and is estimated to be about two solar masses.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] While a rotating neutron star can be slightly more massive, if the compact object is much more massive than the TOV limit, it cannot be a neutron star and is generally expected to be a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] X-ray binaries can be categorised as either *low-mass* or *high-mass*; this classification is based on the mass of the companion star, not the compact object itself.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In a class of X-ray binaries called soft X-ray transients, the companion star is of relatively low mass, allowing for more accurate estimates of the black hole mass.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] These systems actively emit X-rays for only several months once every 10–50 years.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] During the period of low X-ray emission, called quiescence, the accretion disk is extremely faint, allowing detailed observation of the companion star.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Numerous black hole candidates have been measured by this method.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black holes are also sometimes found in binaries with other compact objects, such as white dwarfs, neutron stars, and other black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The centre of nearly every large galaxy contains a supermassive black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The close observational correlation between the mass of this hole and the velocity dispersion of the host galaxy's bulge, known as the M–sigma relation, strongly suggests a connection between the formation of the black hole and that of the galaxy itself.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In some galaxies, the black hole forms a powerful source of radiation called an active galactic nucleus.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Astronomers use the term *active galaxy* to describe galaxies with unusual characteristics, such as unusual spectral line emission and very strong radio emission.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Theoretical and observational studies have shown that the high levels of activity in the centres of these galaxies, regions called active galactic nuclei (AGN), may be explained by accretion onto supermassive black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] These AGN consist of a central black hole that may be millions or billions of times more massive than the Sun, a disk of interstellar gas and dust called an accretion disk, and two jets perpendicular to the accretion disk.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The black holes in quiescent galaxies accrete matter more slowly or radiate less efficiently.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Although supermassive black holes are expected to be found in most AGN, only some galaxies' nuclei have been more carefully studied in attempts to both identify and measure the actual masses of the central supermassive black hole candidates.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Some of the most notable galaxies with supermassive black hole candidates include the Andromeda Galaxy, Messier 32, Messier 87, the Sombrero Galaxy, and the Milky Way itself.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black holes can be detected by gravitational lensing: the deflection of light rays by the deformation of spacetime around a massive object.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A distant star behind a source of gravity may produce multiple images of that star but if the images cannot be resolved, the phenomenon is called microlensing.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In microlensing, astronomers see the star magnified by an amount which changes as the source star, lens, and observer move.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Astronomers must monitor the star image over a few years and match its light curve to models of the gravitational effect.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] As a tool for astrophysics, microlensing is uniquely sensitive to dark objects like isolated black holes not paired in a binary object.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However comparison of the predicted light curve to observations yields multiple indistinguishable solutions, requiring expensive follow-up measurements to select and confirm candidate black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Over 10,000 microlensing events yielded 23 black hole candidates but only one object has been confirmed as an isolated black hole using additional measurements from the Hubble Space Telescope.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Is physical information lost in black holes?
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] According to the no-hair theorem, a black hole is defined by only three parameters: its mass, charge, and angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This seems to mean that all other information about the matter that went into forming the black hole is lost, as there is no way to determine anything about the black hole from outside other than those three parameters.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] When black holes were thought to persist forever, this information loss was not problematic, as the information can be thought of as existing inside the black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However, black holes slowly evaporate by emitting Hawking radiation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This radiation does not appear to carry any additional information about the matter that formed the black hole, meaning that this information is seemingly gone forever.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This is called the black hole information paradox.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Theoretical studies analysing the paradox have led to both further paradoxes and new ideas about the intersection of quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] While there is no consensus on the resolution of the paradox, work on the problem is expected to be important for a theory of quantum gravity.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Observations of faraway galaxies have found that ultraluminous quasars, powered by supermassive black holes, existed in the early universe as far back as redshift $z\geq 7,$ less than a billion years after the Big Bang.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] These black holes have been assumed to be the products of the gravitational collapse of large population III stars.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However, these stellar remnants were not massive enough to produce the quasars observed at early times without accreting beyond the Eddington limit, the theoretical maximum rate of black hole accretion.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Physicists have suggested a variety of different mechanisms by which these supermassive black holes may have formed.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] It has been proposed that smaller black holes may have also undergone mergers to produce the observed supermassive black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] It is also possible that they were seeded by direct-collapse black holes, in which a large cloud of hot gas avoids fragmentation that would lead to multiple stars, due to low angular momentum or heating from a nearby galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Given the right circumstances, a single supermassive star forms and collapses directly into a black hole without undergoing typical stellar evolution.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Additionally, these supermassive black holes in the early universe may be high-mass primordial black holes, which could have accreted further matter in the centres of galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Finally, certain mechanisms allow black holes to grow faster than the theoretical Eddington limit, such as dense gas in the accretion disk limiting outward radiation pressure that prevents the black hole from accreting.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] However, the formation of bipolar jets prevent super-Eddington rates.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] While there is a strong case for supermassive black holes, the dividing line between lighter black holes and neutron stars relies on theories of extremely dense matter.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Direct observational tests are not available: objects observed to have mass higher than the predictions for neutron stars are assumed to be black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Recent evidence from gravitational wave events suggests modifications of these theories may be needed.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] New exotic phases of matter could allow other kinds of massive objects.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Quark stars would be made up of quark matter and supported by quark degeneracy pressure, a form of degeneracy pressure even stronger than neutron degeneracy pressure.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] This would halt gravitational collapse at a higher mass than for a neutron star.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Even stronger stars called electroweak stars would convert quarks in their cores into leptons, providing additional pressure to stop the star from collapsing.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] If, as some extensions of the Standard Model posit, quarks and leptons are made up of the even-smaller fundamental particles called preons, a very compact star could be supported by preon degeneracy pressure.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] While none of these hypothetical models can explain all of the observations of stellar black hole candidates, a Q star is the only alternative which could significantly exceed the mass limit for neutron stars and thus provide an alternative for supermassive black holes.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A few theoretical objects have been conjectured to match observations of astronomical black hole candidates identically or near-identically, but which function via a different mechanism.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A dark energy star would convert infalling matter into vacuum energy; This vacuum energy would be much larger than the vacuum energy of outside space, exerting outwards pressure and preventing a singularity from forming.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A black star would be gravitationally collapsing slowly enough that quantum effects would keep it just on the cusp of fully collapsing into a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] A gravastar would consist of a very thin shell and a dark-energy interior providing outward pressure to stop the collapse into a black hole or formation of a singularity; It could even have another gravastar inside, called a 'nestar'.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] The concept of black holes have inspired artists as well as scientists.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In her book *Conjuring the Void: the Art of Black Holes,* Lynn Gamwell used black holes as an example to explore how art and science interact, considering the application of art to create scientific visualizations and the impact of scientific ideas on art concepts like darkness.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Some science fiction films have incorporated relativity into their black hole visualizations, leading to results similar to images derived from the Event Horizon Telescope.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Fictional treatments of black holes are also used as a mechanism for teaching science.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black holes have been portrayed in science fiction in a variety of ways.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Even before the advent of the term itself, objects with characteristics of black holes appeared in stories.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] In modern day, authors and screenwriters have exploited the relativistic effects of black holes, particularly gravitational time dilation.
[src:astrophysics/black-hole-p02] Black holes have also been appropriated as wormholes or other methods of faster-than-light travel.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] in diameter and approximately 60 million light-years from Earth.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A **galaxy** is a physical system of stars, stellar remnants, interstellar gas, dust, and dark matter bound together by gravity.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The word is derived from the Greek **galaxias** (γαλαξίας), meaning 'milky', a reference to the Milky Way galaxy that contains the Solar System.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Galaxies, averaging an estimated 100 million stars, range in size from dwarfs with less than a thousand stars to the largest galaxies known—supergiants with one hundred trillion stars, each orbiting its galaxy's center of mass.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Most of the mass in a typical galaxy is in the form of dark matter, with only a few percent of that mass visible in the form of stars and nebulae.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Supermassive black holes are a common feature at the centers of galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Galaxies are categorised according to their visual characteristics such as elliptical, spiral, or irregular.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Milky Way is an example of a spiral galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In addition to shape, galaxies may be notable due to special properties, such as interacting with another galaxy, producing stars at an unusual rate, or having an active galactic nucleus.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] It is estimated that there are between 200 billion (2×1011) and 2 trillion galaxies in the observable universe.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Most galaxies are 1,000 to 100,000 parsecs in diameter (approximately 3,000 to 300,000 light years) and are separated by distances in the order of millions of parsecs (or megaparsecs).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] For comparison, the Milky Way has a diameter of at least 26,800 parsecs (87,400 ly).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Its nearest large neighbour, the Andromeda Galaxy, is just over 750,000 parsecs (2.4 million ly) away.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Most galaxies are gravitationally organised into groups, clusters and superclusters.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Milky Way is part of the Local Group, which it dominates along with the Andromeda Galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The group is part of the Virgo Supercluster.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] At the largest scale, these associations are generally arranged into sheets and filaments surrounded by immense voids.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] While there are good models describing the formation of stars from gravitational condensation of dense clouds of gas, galaxy formation is less well understood.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The process operates on the scale of a billion years.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Galaxies occasionally collide during their lifetime.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The word *galaxy* was borrowed via French and Medieval Latin from the Greek term for the Milky Way, **galaxías (kúklos)** γαλαξίας (κύκλος) 'milky (circle)', named after its appearance as a milky band of light in the sky.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In the astronomical literature, the capitalised word "Galaxy" is often used to refer to the Milky Way galaxy, to distinguish it from the other galaxies in the universe.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Galaxies were initially discovered telescopically and were known as *spiral nebulae*.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Most 18th- to 19th-century astronomers considered them as either unresolved star clusters or extragalactic nebulae, but their true composition and natures remained a mystery.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] For this reason they were popularly called *island universes*.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Harlow Shapley began to advocate for the term "galaxy" and against using "universes" and "nebula" for the objects but the very influential Edwin Hubble stuck to nebulae.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The nomenclature did not fully change until after Hubble's death in 1953.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Millions of galaxies have been catalogued, but only a few have well-established names, such as the Andromeda Galaxy, the Magellanic Clouds, the Whirlpool Galaxy, and the Sombrero Galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] All the well-known galaxies appear in one or more of these catalogues but each time under a different number.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] For example, Messier 109 (or "M109") is a spiral galaxy having the number 109 in the catalogue of Messier.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Millions of fainter galaxies are known by their identifiers in sky surveys such as the Sloan Digital Sky Survey.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Greek philosopher Democritus (450–370 BCE) proposed that the bright band on the night sky known as the Milky Way might consist of distant stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] 495–570 CE) was critical of this view, arguing that if the Milky Way was sublunary (situated between Earth and the Moon) it should appear different at different times and places on Earth, and that it should have parallax, which it did not.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In his view, the Milky Way was celestial.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] According to Mohani Mohamed, Arabian astronomer Ibn al-Haytham (965–1037) made the first attempt at observing and measuring the Milky Way's parallax, and he thus "determined that because the Milky Way had no parallax, it must be remote from the Earth, not belonging to the atmosphere".
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Persian astronomer al-Biruni (973–1048) proposed the Milky Way galaxy was "a collection of countless fragments of the nature of nebulous stars." Andalusian astronomer Avempace (d.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] 1138) proposed that it was composed of many stars that almost touched one another, and appeared to be a continuous image due to the effect of refraction from sublunary material, citing his observation of the conjunction of Jupiter and Mars as evidence of this occurring when two objects were near.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Actual proof of the Milky Way consisting of many stars came in 1610 when the Italian astronomer Galileo Galilei used a telescope to study it and discovered it was composed of a huge number of faint stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In his 1755 treatise, Immanuel Kant elaborated on Wright's idea about the Milky Way's structure.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The first project to describe the shape of the Milky Way and the position of the Sun was undertaken by William Herschel in 1785 by counting the number of stars in different regions of the sky.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] He produced a diagram of the shape of the galaxy with the Solar System close to the center.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Using a refined approach, Kapteyn in 1920 arrived at the picture of a small (diameter about 15 kiloparsecs) ellipsoid galaxy with the Sun close to the center.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A different method by Harlow Shapley based on the cataloguing of globular clusters led to a radically different picture: a flat disk with diameter approximately 70 kiloparsecs and the Sun far from the center.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Both analyses failed to take into account the absorption of light by interstellar dust present in the galactic plane; but after Robert Julius Trumpler quantified this effect in 1930 by studying open clusters, the present picture of the Milky Way galaxy emerged.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A few galaxies outside the Milky Way are visible on a dark night to the unaided eye, including the Andromeda Galaxy, Large Magellanic Cloud, Small Magellanic Cloud, and the Triangulum Galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In the 10th century, Persian astronomer Abd al-Rahman al-Sufi made the earliest recorded identification of the Andromeda Galaxy, describing it as a "small cloud".
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 964, he apparently mentioned the Large Magellanic Cloud in his *Book of Fixed Stars*, referring to "Al Bakr of the southern Arabs", since at a declination of about 70° south it was not visible where he lived.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] It was not well known to Europeans until Magellan's voyage in the 16th century.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Andromeda Galaxy was later independently noted by Simon Marius in 1612.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1734, philosopher Emanuel Swedenborg in his *Principia* speculated that there might be other galaxies outside that were formed into galactic clusters which were minuscule parts of the universe extending far beyond what could be seen.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1750, Thomas Wright correctly speculated that the Milky Way was a flattened disk of stars, and that some of the nebulae visible in the night sky might be separate Milky Ways.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Toward the end of the 18th century, Charles Messier compiled a catalog containing the 109 brightest celestial objects having nebulous appearance.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Subsequently, William Herschel assembled a catalog of 5,000 nebulae.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1845, Lord Rosse examined the nebulae catalogued by Herschel and observed the spiral structure of Messier object M51, now known as the Whirlpool Galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Slipher made spectrographic studies of the brightest spiral nebulae to determine their composition.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Slipher discovered that the spiral nebulae have high Doppler shifts, indicating that they are moving at a rate exceeding the velocity of the stars he had measured.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] He found that the majority of these nebulae are moving away from us.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1917, Heber Doust Curtis observed nova S Andromedae within the "Great Andromeda Nebula", as the Andromeda Galaxy, Messier object M31, was then known.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Searching the photographic record, he found 11 more novae.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Curtis noticed that these novae were, on average, 10 magnitudes fainter than those that occurred within this galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] As a result, he was able to come up with a distance estimate of 150,000 parsecs.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] He became a proponent of the so-called "island universes" hypothesis, which holds that spiral nebulae are actually independent galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1920 a debate took place between Harlow Shapley and Heber Curtis, the Great Debate, concerning the nature of the Milky Way, spiral nebulae, and the dimensions of the universe.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] To support his claim that the Great Andromeda Nebula is an external galaxy, Curtis noted the appearance of dark lanes resembling the dust clouds in the Milky Way, as well as the significant Doppler shift.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1922, the Estonian astronomer Ernst Öpik gave a distance determination that supported the theory that the Andromeda Nebula is indeed a distant extra-galactic object.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1926 Hubble produced a classification of galactic morphology that is used to this day.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] shows blue regions containing young, massive stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Advances in astronomy have always been driven by technology.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] After centuries of success in optical astronomy, recent decades have seen major progress in other regions of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The dust present in the interstellar medium is opaque to visual light.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] It is more transparent to far-infrared, which can be used to observe the interior regions of giant molecular clouds and galactic cores in great detail.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Infrared is also used to observe distant, red-shifted galaxies that were formed much earlier.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Water vapor and carbon dioxide absorb a number of useful portions of the infrared spectrum, so high-altitude or space-based telescopes are used for infrared astronomy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The first non-visual study of galaxies, particularly active galaxies, was made using radio frequencies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Earth's atmosphere is nearly transparent to radio between 5 MHz and 30 GHz.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The ionosphere blocks signals below this range.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Combinations of multiple radio telescopes allow very-long-baseline interferometry to map the active jets emitted from active nuclei.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Ultraviolet and X-ray telescopes can observe highly energetic galactic phenomena.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Ultraviolet flares are sometimes observed when a star in a distant galaxy is torn apart from the tidal forces of a nearby black hole.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The distribution of hot gas in galactic clusters can be mapped by X-rays.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The existence of supermassive black holes at the cores of galaxies was confirmed through X-ray astronomy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In 1944, Hendrik van de Hulst predicted that microwave radiation with wavelength of 21 cm would be detectable from interstellar atomic hydrogen gas; and in 1951 it was observed.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This radiation is not affected by dust absorption, and so its Doppler shift can be used to map the motion of the gas in this galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These observations led to the hypothesis of a rotating bar structure in the center of this galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] With improved radio telescopes, hydrogen gas could also be traced in other galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In the 1970s, Vera Rubin uncovered a discrepancy between observed galactic rotation speed and that predicted by the visible mass of stars and gas.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Today, the galaxy rotation problem is thought to be explained by the presence of large quantities of unseen dark matter.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Beginning in the 1990s, the Hubble Space Telescope yielded improved observations.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Among other things, its data helped establish that the missing dark matter in this galaxy could not consist solely of inherently faint and small stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Hubble Deep Field, an extremely long exposure of a relatively empty part of the sky, provided evidence that there are about 125 billion (1.25×1011) galaxies in the observable universe.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Improved technology in detecting the spectra invisible to humans (radio telescopes, infrared cameras, and x-ray telescopes) allows detection of other galaxies that are not detected by Hubble.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Particularly, surveys in the Zone of Avoidance (the region of sky blocked at visible-light wavelengths by the Milky Way) have revealed a number of new galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] However, later observations with the *New Horizons* space probe from outside the zodiacal light observed less cosmic optical light than Conselice while still suggesting that direct observations are missing galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Galaxies come in three main types: ellipticals, spirals, and irregulars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A slightly more extensive description of galaxy types based on their appearance is given by the Hubble sequence.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Since the Hubble sequence is entirely based upon visual morphological type (shape), it may miss certain important characteristics of galaxies such as star formation rate in starburst galaxies and activity in the cores of active galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Many galaxies are thought to contain a supermassive black hole at their center.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This includes the Milky Way, whose core region is called the Galactic Center.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Hubble classification system rates elliptical galaxies on the basis of their ellipticity, ranging from E0, being nearly spherical, up to E7, which is highly elongated.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These galaxies have an ellipsoidal profile, giving them an elliptical appearance regardless of the viewing angle.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Their appearance shows little structure and they typically have relatively little interstellar matter.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Consequently, these galaxies also have a low portion of open clusters and a reduced rate of new star formation.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Instead, they are dominated by generally older, more evolved stars that are orbiting the common center of gravity in random directions.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The stars contain low abundances of heavy elements because star formation ceases after the initial burst.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In this sense they have some similarity to the much smaller globular clusters.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The largest galaxies are the type-cD galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] First described in 1964 by a paper by Thomas A.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Matthews and others, they are a subtype of the more general class of D galaxies, which are giant elliptical galaxies, except that they are much larger.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] They are popularly known as the **supergiant elliptical galaxies** and constitute the largest and most luminous galaxies known.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These galaxies feature a central elliptical nucleus with an extensive, faint halo of stars extending to megaparsec scales.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The profile of their surface brightnesses as a function of their radius (or distance from their cores) falls off more slowly than their smaller counterparts.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The formation of these cD galaxies remains an active area of research, but the leading model is that they are the result of the mergers of smaller galaxies in the environments of dense clusters, or even those outside of clusters with random overdensities.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These processes are the mechanisms that drive the formation of fossil groups or fossil clusters, where a large, relatively isolated, supergiant elliptical resides in the middle of the cluster and are surrounded by an extensive cloud of X-rays as the residue of these galactic collisions.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Another older model posits the phenomenon of cooling flow, where the heated gases in clusters collapses towards their centers as they cool, forming stars in the process, a phenomenon observed in clusters such as Perseus, and more recently in the Phoenix Cluster.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A shell galaxy is a type of elliptical galaxy where the stars in its halo are arranged in concentric shells.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] About one-tenth of elliptical galaxies have a shell-like structure, which has never been observed in spiral galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] For example, galaxy NGC 3923 has over 20 shells.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Spiral galaxies resemble spiraling pinwheels.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Though the stars and other visible material contained in such a galaxy lie mostly on a plane, the majority of mass in spiral galaxies exists in a roughly spherical halo of dark matter which extends beyond the visible component, as demonstrated by the universal rotation curve concept.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Spiral galaxies consist of a rotating disk of stars and interstellar medium, along with a central bulge of generally older stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Extending outward from the bulge are relatively bright arms.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In the Hubble classification scheme, spiral galaxies are listed as type *S*, followed by a letter (*a*, *b*, or *c*) which indicates the degree of tightness of the spiral arms and the size of the central bulge.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] An *Sa* galaxy has tightly wound, poorly defined arms and possesses a relatively large core region.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] At the other extreme, an *Sc* galaxy has open, well-defined arms and a small core region.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A galaxy with poorly defined arms is sometimes referred to as a flocculent spiral galaxy; in contrast to the grand design spiral galaxy that has prominent and well-defined spiral arms.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The speed in which a galaxy rotates is thought to correlate with the flatness of the disc as some spiral galaxies have thick bulges, while others are thin and dense.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In spiral galaxies, the spiral arms do have the shape of approximate logarithmic spirals, a pattern that can be theoretically shown to result from a disturbance in a uniformly rotating mass of stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Like the stars, the spiral arms rotate around the center, but they do so with constant angular velocity.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The spiral arms are thought to be areas of high-density matter, or "density waves".
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] As stars move through an arm, the space velocity of each stellar system is modified by the gravitational force of the higher density.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] (The velocity returns to normal after the stars depart on the other side of the arm.) This effect is akin to a "wave" of slowdowns moving along a highway full of moving cars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The arms are visible because the high density facilitates star formation, and therefore they harbor many bright and young stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A majority of spiral galaxies, including the Milky Way galaxy, have a linear, bar-shaped band of stars that extends outward to either side of the core, then merges into the spiral arm structure.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In the Hubble classification scheme, these are designated by an *SB*, followed by a lower-case letter (*a*, *b* or *c*) which indicates the form of the spiral arms (in the same manner as the categorization of normal spiral galaxies).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Bars are thought to be temporary structures that can occur as a result of a density wave radiating outward from the core, or else due to a tidal interaction with another galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Many barred spiral galaxies are active, possibly as a result of gas being channeled into the core along the arms.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Milky Way is a large disk-shaped barred-spiral galaxy about 30 kiloparsecs in diameter and a kiloparsec thick.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] It contains about two hundred billion (2×1011) stars and has a total mass of about six hundred billion (6×1011) times the mass of the Sun.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Recently, researchers described galaxies called super-luminous spirals.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] They are very large with an upward diameter of 437,000 light-years (compared to the Milky Way's 87,400 light-year diameter).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] With a mass of 340 billion solar masses, they generate a significant amount of ultraviolet and mid-infrared light.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] They are thought to have an increased star formation rate around 30 times faster than the Milky Way.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Despite the prominence of large elliptical and spiral galaxies, most galaxies are dwarf galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] They are relatively small when compared with other galactic formations, being about one hundredth the size of the Milky Way, with only a few billion stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Blue compact dwarf galaxies contains large clusters of young, hot, massive stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Ultra-compact dwarf galaxies have been discovered that are only 100 parsecs across.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Many dwarf galaxies may orbit a single larger galaxy; the Milky Way has at least a dozen such satellites, with an estimated 300–500 yet to be discovered.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Most of the information we have about dwarf galaxies come from observations of the Local Group, containing two spiral galaxies, the Milky Way and Andromeda, and many dwarf galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These dwarf galaxies are classified as either irregular or dwarf elliptical/dwarf spheroidal galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A study of 27 Milky Way neighbors found that in all dwarf galaxies, the central mass is approximately 10 million solar masses, regardless of whether it has thousands or millions of stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This suggests that galaxies are largely formed by dark matter, and that the minimum size may indicate a form of warm dark matter incapable of gravitational coalescence on a smaller scale.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Interactions between galaxies are relatively frequent, and they can play an important role in galactic evolution.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Near misses between galaxies result in warping distortions due to tidal interactions, and may cause some exchange of gas and dust.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Collisions occur when two galaxies pass directly through each other and have sufficient relative momentum not to merge.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The stars of interacting galaxies usually do not collide, but the gas and dust within the two forms interacts, sometimes triggering star formation.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A collision can severely distort the galaxies' shapes, forming bars, rings or tail-like structures.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] At the extreme of interactions are galactic mergers, where the galaxies' relative momentums are insufficient to allow them to pass through each other.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Instead, they gradually merge to form a single, larger galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Mergers can result in significant changes to the galaxies' original morphology.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] If one of the galaxies is much more massive than the other, the result is known as cannibalism, where the more massive larger galaxy remains relatively undisturbed, and the smaller one is torn apart.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Milky Way galaxy is currently in the process of cannibalizing the Sagittarius Dwarf Elliptical Galaxy and the Canis Major Dwarf Galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Stars are created within galaxies from a reserve of cold gas that forms giant molecular clouds.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Some galaxies have been observed to form stars at an exceptional rate, which is known as a *starburst*.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] If they continue to do so, they would consume their reserve of gas in a time span less than the galaxy's lifespan.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Hence starburst activity usually lasts only about ten million years, a relatively brief period in a galaxy's history.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Starburst galaxies were more common during the universe's early history, but still contribute an estimated 15% to total star production.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Starburst galaxies are characterized by dusty concentrations of gas and the appearance of newly formed stars, including massive stars that ionize the surrounding clouds to create H II regions.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These stars produce supernova explosions, creating expanding remnants that interact powerfully with the surrounding gas.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These outbursts trigger a chain reaction of star-building that spreads throughout the gaseous region.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Only when the available gas is nearly consumed or dispersed does the activity end.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Starbursts are often associated with merging or interacting galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The prototype example of such a starburst-forming interaction is M82, which experienced a close encounter with the larger M81.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Irregular galaxies often exhibit spaced knots of starburst activity.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A radio galaxy is a galaxy with giant regions of radio emission extending well beyond its visible structure.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These energetic radio lobes are powered by jets from its active galactic nucleus.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Radio galaxies are classified according to their Fanaroff–Riley classification.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The **FR I** class have lower radio luminosity and exhibit structures which are more elongated; the **FR II** class are higher radio luminosity.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The correlation of radio luminosity and structure suggests that the sources in these two types of galaxies may differ.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Radio galaxies can also be classified as giant radio galaxies (GRGs), whose radio emissions can extend to scales of megaparsecs (3.26 million light-years).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Alcyoneus is an FR II class low-excitation radio galaxy which has the largest observed radio emission, with lobed structures spanning 5 megaparsecs (16×106 ly).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] For comparison, another similarly sized giant radio galaxy is 3C 236, with lobes 15 million light-years across.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] It should however be noted that radio emissions are *not* always considered part of the main galaxy itself.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A giant radio galaxy is a special class of objects characterized by the presence of radio lobes generated by relativistic jets powered by the central galaxy's supermassive black hole.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Giant radio galaxies are different from ordinary radio galaxies in that they can extend to much larger scales, reaching upwards to several megaparsecs across, far larger than the diameters of their host galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A "normal" radio galaxy is defined by where the radio energy source is not a supermassive black hole or monster neutron star; instead, its emissions arise from synchrotron radiation produced by relativistic electrons accelerated by supernova.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These sources are comparatively short lived, making the radio spectrum from normal radio galaxies an especially good way to study star formation.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Some observable galaxies are classified as "active" if they contain an active galactic nucleus (AGN).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A significant portion of the galaxy's total energy output is emitted by the active nucleus instead of its stars, dust and interstellar medium.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] There are multiple classification and naming schemes for AGNs, but those in the lower ranges of luminosity are called Seyfert galaxies, while those with luminosities much greater than that of the host galaxy are known as quasi-stellar objects or quasars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Models of AGNs suggest that a significant fraction of their light is shifted to far-infrared frequencies because optical and UV emission in the nucleus is absorbed and remitted by dust and gas surrounding it.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The standard model for an active galactic nucleus is based on an accretion disc that forms around a supermassive black hole (SMBH) at the galaxy's core region.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The radiation from an active galactic nucleus results from the gravitational energy of matter as it falls toward the black hole from the disc.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The AGN's luminosity depends on the SMBH's mass and the rate at which matter falls onto it.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In about 10% of these galaxies, a diametrically opposed pair of energetic jets ejects particles from the galaxy core at velocities close to the speed of light.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The mechanism for producing these jets is not well understood.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Seyfert galaxies are one of the two largest groups of active galaxies, along with quasars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] They have quasar-like nuclei (very luminous, distant and bright sources of electromagnetic radiation) with very high surface brightnesses; but unlike quasars, their host galaxies are clearly detectable.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Seen through a telescope, a Seyfert galaxy appears like an ordinary galaxy with a bright star superimposed atop the core.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Seyfert galaxies are divided into two principal subtypes based on the frequencies observed in their spectra.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Quasars are the most energetic and distant members of active galactic nuclei.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Extremely luminous, they were first identified as high redshift sources of electromagnetic energy, including radio waves and visible light, that appeared more similar to stars than to extended sources similar to galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Their luminosity can be 100 times that of the Milky Way.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The nearest known quasar, Markarian 231, is about 581 million light-years from Earth, while others have been discovered as far away as UHZ1, roughly 13.2 billion light-years distant.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Quasars are noteworthy for providing the first demonstration of the phenomenon that gravity can act as a lens for light.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Blazars are believed to be active galaxies with a relativistic jet pointed in the direction of Earth.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A radio galaxy emits radio frequencies from relativistic jets.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A unified model of these types of active galaxies explains their differences based on the observer's position.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Possibly related to active galactic nuclei (as well as starburst regions) are low-ionization nuclear emission-line regions (LINERs).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The emission from LINER-type galaxies is dominated by weakly ionized elements.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The excitation sources for the weakly ionized lines include post-AGB stars, AGN, and shocks.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Approximately one-third of nearby galaxies are classified as containing LINER nuclei.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Luminous infrared galaxies (LIRGs) are galaxies with luminosities—the measurement of electromagnetic power output—above 1011 L☉ (solar luminosities).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In most cases, most of their energy comes from large numbers of young stars which heat surrounding dust, which reradiates the energy in the infrared.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Luminosity high enough to be a LIRG requires a star formation rate of at least 18 M☉ yr−1.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Ultra-luminous infrared galaxies (ULIRGs) are at least ten times more luminous still and form stars at rates >180 M☉ yr−1.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Many LIRGs also emit radiation from an AGN.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Infrared galaxies emit more energy in the infrared than all other wavelengths combined, with peak emission typically at wavelengths of 60 to 100 microns.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] LIRGs are believed to be created from the strong interaction and merger of spiral galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] While uncommon in the local universe, LIRGs and ULIRGS were more prevalent when the universe was younger.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Galaxies do not have a definite boundary by their nature, and are characterized by a gradually decreasing stellar density as a function of increasing distance from their center, making measurements of their true extents difficult.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Nevertheless, astronomers over the past few decades have made several criteria in defining the sizes of galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] As early as the time of Edwin Hubble in 1936, there have been attempts to characterize the diameters of galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The earliest efforts were based on the observed angle subtended by the galaxy and its estimated distance, leading to an *angular diameter* (also called "metric diameter").
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The *isophotal diameter* is introduced as a conventional way of measuring a galaxy's size based on its apparent surface brightness.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Isophotes are curves in a diagram—such as a picture of a galaxy—that adjoins points of equal brightnesses, and are useful in defining the extent of the galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The apparent brightness flux of a galaxy is measured in units of magnitudes per square arcsecond (mag/arcsec2; sometimes expressed as *mag arcsec−2*), which defines the brightness depth of the isophote.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] To illustrate how this unit works, a typical galaxy has a brightness flux of 18 mag/arcsec2 at its central region.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This brightness is equivalent to the light of an 18th magnitude hypothetical point object (like a star) being spread out evenly in a one square arcsecond area of the sky.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The isophotal diameter is typically defined as the region enclosing all the light down to 25 mag/arcsec2 in the blue B-band, which is then referred to as the D25 standard.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The half-light radius (also known as *effective radius*; R*e*) is a measure that is based on the galaxy's overall brightness flux.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This is the radius upon which half, or 50%, of the total brightness flux of the galaxy was emitted.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This was first proposed by Gérard de Vaucouleurs in 1948.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The choice of using 50% was arbitrary, but proved to be useful in further works by R.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Fish in 1963, where he established a luminosity concentration law that relates the brightnesses of elliptical galaxies and their respective R*e*, and by José Luis Sérsic in 1968 that defined a mass-radius relation in galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Using half-light radius allows a rough estimate of a galaxy's size, but is not particularly helpful in determining its morphology.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In particular, in the ESO-Uppsala Catalogue of Galaxies values of 50%, 70%, and 90% of the total blue light (the light detected through a B-band specific filter) had been used to calculate a galaxy's diameter.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] First described by Vahe Petrosian in 1976, a modified version of this method has been used by the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This method employs a mathematical model on a galaxy whose radius is determined by the azimuthally (horizontal) averaged profile of its brightness flux.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In particular, the SDSS employed the Petrosian magnitude in the R-band (658 nm, in the red part of the visible spectrum) to ensure that the brightness flux of a galaxy would be captured as much as possible while counteracting the effects of background noise.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] For a galaxy whose brightness profile is exponential, it is expected to capture all of its brightness flux, and 80% for galaxies that follow a profile that follows de Vaucouleurs's law.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Petrosian magnitudes have the advantage of being redshift and distance independent, allowing the measurement of the galaxy's apparent size since the Petrosian radius is defined in terms of the galaxy's overall luminous flux.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A critique of an earlier version of this method has been issued by the Infrared Processing and Analysis Center, with the method causing a magnitude of error (upwards to 10%) of the values than using isophotal diameter.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The use of Petrosian magnitudes also have the disadvantage of missing most of the light outside the Petrosian aperture, which is defined relative to the galaxy's overall brightness profile, especially for elliptical galaxies, with higher signal-to-noise ratios on higher distances and redshifts.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A correction for this method has been issued by Graham *et al.* in 2005, based on the assumption that galaxies follow Sérsic's law.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This method has been used by 2MASS as an adaptation from the previously used methods of isophotal measurement.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Since 2MASS operates in the near infrared, which has the advantage of being able to recognize dimmer, cooler, and older stars, it has a different form of approach compared to other methods that normally use B-filter.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The detail of the method used by 2MASS has been described thoroughly in a document by Jarrett *et al.*, with the survey measuring several parameters.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The standard aperture ellipse (area of detection) is defined by the infrared isophote at the Ks band (roughly 2.2 μm wavelength) of 20 mag/arcsec2.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] is an example of a compact galaxy group.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Deep-sky surveys show that galaxies are often found in groups and clusters.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Solitary galaxies that have not significantly interacted with other galaxies of comparable mass in the past few billion years are relatively scarce.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Only about 5% of the galaxies surveyed are isolated in this sense.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] However, they may have interacted and even merged with other galaxies in the past, and may still be orbited by smaller satellite galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] On the largest scale, the universe is continually expanding, resulting in an average increase in the separation between individual galaxies (see Hubble's law).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Associations of galaxies can overcome this expansion on a local scale through their mutual gravitational attraction.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These associations formed early, as clumps of dark matter pulled their respective galaxies together.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Nearby groups later merged to form larger-scale clusters.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] This ongoing merging process, as well as an influx of infalling gas, heats the intergalactic gas in a cluster to very high temperatures of 30–100 megakelvins.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] About 70–80% of a cluster's mass is in the form of dark matter, with 10–30% consisting of this heated gas and the remaining few percent in the form of galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Most galaxies are gravitationally bound to a number of other galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] These form a fractal-like hierarchical distribution of clustered structures, with the smallest such associations being termed groups.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A group of galaxies is the most common type of galactic cluster; these formations contain the majority of galaxies (as well as most of the baryonic mass) in the universe.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] To remain gravitationally bound to such a group, each member galaxy must have a sufficiently low velocity to prevent it from escaping (see Virial theorem).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] If there is insufficient kinetic energy, however, the group may evolve into a smaller number of galaxies through mergers.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Clusters of galaxies consist of hundreds to thousands of galaxies bound together by gravity.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Clusters of galaxies are often dominated by a single giant elliptical galaxy, known as the brightest cluster galaxy, which, over time, tidally destroys its satellite galaxies and adds their mass to its own.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Superclusters contain tens of thousands of galaxies, which are found in clusters, groups and sometimes individually.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] At the supercluster scale, galaxies are arranged into sheets and filaments surrounding vast empty voids.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Above this scale, the universe appears to be the same in all directions (isotropic and homogeneous), though this notion has been challenged in recent years by numerous findings of large-scale structures that appear to be exceeding this scale.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Hercules–Corona Borealis Great Wall, currently the largest structure in the universe found so far, is 10 billion light-years (three gigaparsecs) in length.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Milky Way galaxy is a member of an association named the Local Group, a relatively small group of galaxies that has a diameter of approximately one megaparsec.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Milky Way and the Andromeda Galaxy are the two brightest galaxies within the group; many of the other member galaxies are dwarf companions of these two.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The Local Group itself is a part of a cloud-like structure within the Virgo Supercluster, a large, extended structure of groups and clusters of galaxies centered on the Virgo Cluster.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In turn, the Virgo Supercluster is a portion of the Laniakea Supercluster.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Galaxies have magnetic fields of their own.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] A galaxy's magnetic field influences its dynamics in multiple ways, including affecting the formation of spiral arms and transporting angular momentum in gas clouds.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The latter effect is particularly important, as it is a necessary factor for the gravitational collapse of those clouds, and thus for star formation.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The typical average equipartition strength for spiral galaxies is about 10 μG (microgauss) or 1 nT (nanotesla).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] By comparison, the Earth's magnetic field has an average strength of about 0.3 G (Gauss) or 30 μT (microtesla).
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] Radio-faint galaxies like M 31 and M33, the Milky Way's neighbors, have weaker fields (about 5 μG), while gas-rich galaxies with high star-formation rates, like M 51, M 83 and NGC 6946, have 15 μG on average.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] In prominent spiral arms, the field strength can be up to 25 μG, in regions where cold gas and dust are also concentrated.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p01] The strongest total equipartition fields (50–100 μG) were found in starburst galaxies—for example, in M 82 and the Antennae; and in nuclear starburst regions, such as the centers of NGC 1097 and other barred galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Current models of the formation of galaxies in the early universe are based on the ΛCDM model.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] About 300,000 years after the Big Bang, atoms of hydrogen and helium began to form, in an event called recombination.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Nearly all the hydrogen was neutral (non-ionized) and readily absorbed light, and no stars had yet formed.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] As a result, this period has been called the "dark ages".
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] It was from density fluctuations (or anisotropic irregularities) in this primordial matter that larger structures began to appear.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] As a result, masses of baryonic matter started to condense within cold dark matter halos.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] These primordial structures allowed gasses to condense in to protogalaxies, large scale gas clouds that were precursors to the first galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] As gas falls in to the gravity of the dark matter halos, its pressure and temperature rise.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] To condense further, the gas must radiate energy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] This process was slow in the early universe dominated by hydrogen atoms and molecules which are inefficient radiators compared to heavier elements.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] As clumps of gas aggregate forming rotating disks, temperatures and pressures continue to increase.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Some places within the disk reach high enough density to form stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Once protogalaxies began to form and contract, the first halo stars, called Population III stars, appeared within them.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] These were composed of primordial gas, almost entirely of hydrogen and helium.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] The most massive stars collapse in violent supernova explosions releasing heavy elements ("metals") into the interstellar medium.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] This metal content is incorporated into population II stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Theoretical models for early galaxy formation have been verified and informed by a large number and variety of sophisticated astronomical observations.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] The photometric observations generally need spectroscopic confirmation due to the large number mechanisms that can introduce systematic errors.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] For example, a high redshift (z ~ 16) photometric observation by James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) was later corrected to be closer to z ~ 5.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Nevertheless, confirmed observations from the JWST and other observatories are accumulating, allowing systematic comparison of early galaxies to predictions of theory.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Evidence for individual Population III stars in early galaxies is even more challenging.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Even seemingly confirmed spectroscopic evidence may turn out to have other origins.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] For example, astronomers reported HeII emission evidence for Population III stars in the Cosmos Redshift 7 galaxy, with a redshift value of 6.60.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Subsequent observations found metallic emission lines, OIII, inconsistent with an early-galaxy star.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Once stars begin to form, emit radiation, and in some cases explode, the process of galaxy formation becomes very complex, involving interactions between the forces of gravity, radiation, and thermal energy.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Many details are still poorly understood.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Within a billion years of a galaxy's formation, key structures begin to appear.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Globular clusters, the central supermassive black hole, and a galactic bulge of metal-poor Population II stars form.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] The creation of a supermassive black hole appears to play a key role in actively regulating the growth of galaxies by limiting the total amount of additional matter added.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] During this early epoch, galaxies undergo a major burst of star formation.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] During the following two billion years, the accumulated matter settles into a galactic disc.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] A galaxy will continue to absorb infalling material from high-velocity clouds and dwarf galaxies throughout its life.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] This matter is mostly hydrogen and helium.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] The cycle of stellar birth and death slowly increases the abundance of heavy elements, eventually allowing the formation of planets.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] is estimated to contain 200 billion to two trillion galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Star formation rates in galaxies depend upon their local environment.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Isolated 'void' galaxies have highest rate per stellar mass, with 'field' galaxies associated with spiral galaxies having lower rates and galaxies in dense cluster having the lowest rates.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] The evolution of galaxies can be significantly affected by interactions and collisions.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Mergers of galaxies were common during the early epoch, and the majority of galaxies were peculiar in morphology.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Given the distances between the stars, the great majority of stellar systems in colliding galaxies will be unaffected.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] However, gravitational stripping of the interstellar gas and dust that makes up the spiral arms produces a long train of stars known as tidal tails.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Examples of these formations can be seen in NGC 4676 or the Antennae Galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] The Milky Way galaxy and the nearby Andromeda Galaxy are moving toward each other at about 130 km/s, and—depending upon the lateral movements—the two might collide in about five to six billion years.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Although the Milky Way has never collided with a galaxy as large as Andromeda before, it has collided and merged with other galaxies in the past.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Cosmological simulations indicate that, 11 billion years ago, it merged with a particularly large galaxy that has been labeled the Kraken.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] As time passes, mergers of two systems of equal size become less common.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Most bright galaxies have remained fundamentally unchanged for the last few billion years, and the net rate of star formation probably also peaked about ten billion years ago.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Spiral galaxies, like the Milky Way, produce new generations of stars as long as they have dense molecular clouds of interstellar hydrogen in their spiral arms.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Elliptical galaxies are largely devoid of this gas, and so form few new stars.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] The supply of star-forming material is finite; once stars have converted the available supply of hydrogen into heavier elements, new star formation will come to an end.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] At the end of the stellar age, galaxies will be composed of compact objects: brown dwarfs, white dwarfs that are cooling or cold ("black dwarfs"), neutron stars, and black holes.
[src:astrophysics/galaxy-p02] Eventually, as a result of gravitational relaxation, all stars will either fall into central supermassive black holes or be flung into intergalactic space as a result of collisions.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The **interstellar medium** (**ISM**) is the matter and radiation that exists in the space between the star systems in a galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This matter includes gas in ionic, atomic, and molecular form, as well as dust and cosmic rays.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] It fills interstellar space and blends smoothly into the surrounding intergalactic medium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The energy that occupies the same volume, in the form of electromagnetic radiation, is the **interstellar radiation field**.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The interstellar medium is composed of multiple phases distinguished by whether matter is ionic, atomic, or molecular, and the temperature and density of the matter.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The interstellar medium is composed primarily of hydrogen, followed by helium with trace amounts of carbon, oxygen, and nitrogen.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The thermal pressures of these phases are in rough equilibrium with one another.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Magnetic fields and turbulent motions also provide pressure in the ISM, and are typically more important, dynamically, than the thermal pressure.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In the interstellar medium, matter is primarily in molecular form and reaches number densities of 1012 molecules per m3 (1 trillion molecules per m3).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In hot, diffuse regions, gas is highly ionized, and the density may be as low as 100 ions per m3.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Compare this with a number density of roughly 1025 molecules per m3 for air at sea level, and 1016 molecules per m3 (10 quadrillion molecules per m3) for a laboratory high-vacuum chamber.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Within our galaxy, by mass, 99% of the ISM is gas in any form, and 1% is dust.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Of the gas in the ISM, by number 91% of atoms are hydrogen and 8.9% are helium, with 0.1% being atoms of elements heavier than hydrogen or helium, known as "metals" in astronomical parlance.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] By mass this amounts to 70% hydrogen, 28% helium, and 1.5% heavier elements.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The hydrogen and helium are primarily a result of primordial nucleosynthesis, while the heavier elements in the ISM are mostly a result of enrichment (due to stellar nucleosynthesis) in the process of stellar evolution.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The ISM plays a crucial role in astrophysics precisely because of its intermediate role between stellar and galactic scales.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Stars form within the densest regions of the ISM, which ultimately contributes to molecular clouds and replenishes the ISM with matter and energy through planetary nebulae, stellar winds, and supernovae.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This interplay between stars and the ISM helps determine the rate at which a galaxy depletes its gaseous content, and therefore its lifespan of active star formation.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] *Voyager 1* reached the ISM on August 25, 2012, making it the first artificial object from Earth to do so.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Interstellar plasma and dust will be studied until the estimated mission end date of 2025.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Its twin *Voyager 2* entered the ISM on November 5, 2018.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Table 1 shows a breakdown of the properties of the components of the ISM of the Milky Way.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Field, Goldsmith & Habing (1969) put forward the static two *phase* equilibrium model to explain the observed properties of the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Their modeled ISM included a cold dense phase (*T* < 300 K), consisting of clouds of neutral and molecular hydrogen, and a warm intercloud phase (*T* ~ 104 K), consisting of rarefied neutral and ionized gas.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] McKee & Ostriker (1977) added a dynamic third phase that represented the very hot (*T* ~ 106 K) gas that had been shock heated by supernovae and constituted most of the volume of the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These phases are the temperatures where heating and cooling can reach a stable equilibrium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Their paper formed the basis for further study over the subsequent three decades.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] However, the relative proportions of the phases and their subdivisions are still not well understood.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The basic physics behind these phases can be understood through the behaviour of hydrogen, since this is by far the largest constituent of the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The different phases are roughly in pressure balance over most of the Galactic disk, since regions of excess pressure will expand and cool, and likewise under-pressure regions will be compressed and heated.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Therefore, since *P = n k T*, hot regions (high *T*) generally have low particle number density *n*.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Coronal gas has low enough density that collisions between particles are rare and so little radiation is produced, hence there is little loss of energy and the temperature can stay high for periods of hundreds of millions of years.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In contrast, once the temperature falls to O(105 K) with correspondingly higher density, protons and electrons can recombine to form hydrogen atoms, emitting photons which take energy out of the gas, leading to runaway cooling.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Left to itself this would produce the warm neutral medium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] However, OB stars are so hot that some of their photons have energy greater than the Lyman limit, *E* > 13.6 eV, enough to ionize hydrogen.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This *ionization front* marks the boundary between the Warm ionized and Warm neutral medium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] OB stars, and also cooler ones, produce many more photons with energies below the Lyman limit, which pass through the ionized region almost unabsorbed.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Some of these have high enough energy (> 11.3 eV) to ionize carbon atoms, creating a C II ("ionized carbon") region outside the (hydrogen) ionization front.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In dense regions this may also be limited in size by the availability of photons, but often such photons can penetrate throughout the neutral phase and only get absorbed in the outer layers of molecular clouds.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Photons with *E* > 4 eV or so can break up molecules such as H2 and CO, creating a photodissociation region (PDR) which is more or less equivalent to the Warm neutral medium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These processes contribute to the heating of the WNM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The distinction between Warm and Cold neutral medium is again due to a range of temperature/density in which runaway cooling occurs.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The densest molecular clouds have significantly higher pressure than the interstellar average, since they are bound together by their own gravity.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] When stars form in such clouds, especially OB stars, they convert the surrounding gas into the warm ionized phase, a temperature increase of several hundred.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Initially the gas is still at molecular cloud densities, and so at vastly higher pressure than the ISM average: this is a classical H II region.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The large overpressure causes the ionized gas to expand away from the remaining molecular gas (a Champagne flow), and the flow will continue until either the molecular cloud is fully evaporated or the OB stars reach the end of their lives, after a few millions years.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] At this point the OB stars explode as supernovas, creating blast waves in the warm gas that increase temperatures to the coronal phase (supernova remnants, SNR).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These too expand and cool over several million years until they return to average ISM pressure.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Most discussion of the ISM concerns spiral galaxies like the Milky Way, in which nearly all the mass in the ISM is confined to a relatively thin disk, typically with scale height about 100 parsecs (300 light years), which can be compared to a typical disk diameter of 30,000 parsecs.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Gas and stars in the disk orbit the galactic centre with typical orbital speeds of 200 km/s.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This is much faster than the random motions of atoms in the ISM, but since the orbital motion of the gas is coherent, the average motion does not directly affect structure in the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The vertical scale height of the ISM is set in roughly the same way as the Earth's atmosphere, as a balance between the local gravitation field (dominated by the stars in the disk) and the pressure.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Further from the disk plane, the ISM is mainly in the low-density warm and coronal phases, which extend at least several thousand parsecs away from the disk plane.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This galactic halo or 'corona' also contains significant magnetic field and cosmic ray energy density.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The rotation of galaxy disks influences ISM structures in several ways.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Spiral arms are due to perturbations in the disk orbits - essentially ripples in the disk, that cause orbits to alternately converge and diverge, compressing and then expanding the local ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The visible spiral arms are the regions of maximum density, and the compression often triggers star formation in molecular clouds, leading to an abundance of H II regions along the arms.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Coriolis force also influences large ISM features.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Irregular galaxies such as the Magellanic Clouds have similar interstellar mediums to spirals, but less organized.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In elliptical galaxies the ISM is almost entirely in the coronal phase, since there is no coherent disk motion to support cold gas far from the center: instead, the scale height of the ISM must be comperable to the radius of the galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This is consistent with the observation that there is little sign of current star formation in ellipticals.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Some elliptical galaxies do show evidence for a small disk component, with ISM similar to spirals, buried close to their centers.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The ISM of lenticular galaxies, as with their other properties, appear intermediate between spirals and ellipticals.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Very close to the center of most galaxies (within a few hundred light years at most), the ISM is profoundly modified by the central supermassive black hole: see Galactic Center for the Milky Way, and Active galactic nucleus for extreme examples in other galaxies.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The rest of this article will focus on the ISM in the disk plane of spirals, far from the galactic center.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Astronomers describe the ISM as turbulent, meaning that the gas has quasi-random motions coherent over a large range of spatial scales.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Unlike normal turbulence, in which the fluid motions are highly subsonic, the bulk motions of the ISM are usually larger than the sound speed.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In the ISM this is further complicated by the magnetic field, which provides wave modes such as Alfvén waves which are often faster than pure sound waves: if turbulent speeds are supersonic but below the Alfvén wave speed, the behaviour is more like subsonic turbulence.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Stars are born deep inside large complexes of molecular clouds, typically a few parsecs in size.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] During their lives and deaths, stars interact physically with the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Stellar winds from young clusters of stars (often with giant or supergiant HII regions surrounding them) and shock waves created by supernovae inject enormous amounts of energy into their surroundings, which leads to hypersonic turbulence.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The resultant structures – of varying sizes – can be observed, such as stellar wind bubbles and superbubbles of hot gas, seen by X-ray satellite telescopes or turbulent flows observed in radio telescope maps.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Stars and planets, once formed, are unaffected by pressure forces in the ISM, and so do not take part in the turbulent motions, although stars formed in molecular clouds in a galactic disk share their general orbital motion around the galaxy center.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Thus stars are usually in motion relative to their surrounding ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The Sun is currently traveling through the Local Interstellar Cloud, an irregular clump of the warm neutral medium a few parsecs across, within the low-density Local Bubble, a 100-parsec radius region of coronal gas.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In October 2020, astronomers reported a significant unexpected increase in density in the space beyond the Solar System as detected by the *Voyager 1* and *Voyager 2* space probes.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] According to the researchers, this implies that "the density gradient is a large-scale feature of the VLISM (very local interstellar medium) in the general direction of the heliospheric nose".
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The interstellar medium begins where the interplanetary medium of the Solar System ends.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The solar wind slows to subsonic velocities at the termination shock, 90–100 astronomical units from the Sun.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In the region beyond the termination shock, called the heliosheath, interstellar matter interacts with the solar wind.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] *Voyager 1*, the farthest human-made object from the Earth (after 1998), crossed the termination shock December 16, 2004 and later entered interstellar space when it crossed the heliopause on August 25, 2012, providing the first direct probe of conditions in the ISM (Stone et al.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Dust grains in the ISM are responsible for extinction and reddening, the decreasing light intensity and shift in the dominant observable wavelengths of light from a star.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These effects are caused by scattering and absorption of photons and allow the ISM to be observed with the naked eye in a dark sky.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The apparent rifts that can be seen in the band of the Milky Way – a uniform disk of stars – are caused by absorption of background starlight by dust in molecular clouds within a few thousand light years from Earth.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This effect decreases rapidly with increasing wavelength ("reddening" is caused by greater absorption of blue than red light), and becomes almost negligible at mid-infrared wavelengths (> 5 μm).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Extinction provides one of the best ways of mapping the three-dimensional structure of the ISM, especially since the advent of accurate distances to millions of stars from the *Gaia* mission.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The total amount of dust in front of each star is determined from its reddening, and the dust is then located along the line of sight by comparing the dust column density in front of stars projected close together on the sky, but at different distances.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] By 2022 it was possible to generate a map of ISM structures within 3 kpc (10,000 light years) of the Sun.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Far ultraviolet light is absorbed effectively by the neutral hydrogen gas in the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Specifically, atomic hydrogen absorbs very strongly at about 121.5 nanometers, the Lyman-alpha transition, and also at the other Lyman series lines.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Therefore, it is nearly impossible to see light emitted at those wavelengths from a star farther than a few hundred light years from Earth, because most of it is absorbed during the trip to Earth by intervening neutral hydrogen.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] All photons with wavelength < 91.6 nm, the Lyman limit, can ionize hydrogen and are also very strongly absorbed.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The absorption gradually decreases with increasing photon energy, and the ISM begins to become transparent again in soft X-rays, with wavelengths shorter than about 1 nm.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The ISM is usually far from thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] However, the interstellar radiation field is typically much weaker than a medium in thermodynamic equilibrium; it is most often roughly that of an A star (surface temperature of ~10,000 K) highly diluted.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Therefore, bound levels within an atom or molecule in the ISM are rarely populated according to the Boltzmann formula (Spitzer 1978, § 2.4).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Depending on the temperature, density, and ionization state of a portion of the ISM, different heating and cooling mechanisms determine the temperature of the gas.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Cosmic rays are an efficient heating source able to penetrate in the depths of molecular clouds.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] ) are more important because they are far more numerous than high-energy cosmic rays.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] is absorbed by the dust grain, and some of its energy is used to overcome the potential energy barrier and remove the electron from the grain.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] which heats the gas through collisions with other particles.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This indicates that the smallest dust grains dominate this method of heating.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] , and those photoelectrons can provoke secondary ionizations.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] As the intensity is often low, this heating is only efficient in warm, less dense atomic medium (as the column density is small).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] can penetrate and x-ray heating can be ignored.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] atoms (which can travel over the grain) meet.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] molecule, as well as heating the dust grain.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This kinetic energy, as well as the energy transferred from de-excitation of the hydrogen molecule through collisions, heats the gas.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Collisions at high densities between gas atoms and molecules with dust grains can transfer thermal energy.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This is not important in HII regions because UV radiation is more important.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] It is also less important in diffuse ionized medium due to the low density.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In the neutral diffuse medium grains are always colder, but do not effectively cool the gas due to the low densities.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Grain heating by thermal exchange is very important in supernova remnants where densities and temperatures are very high.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Gas heating via grain-gas collisions is dominant deep in giant molecular clouds (especially at high densities).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Far infrared radiation penetrates deeply due to the low optical depth.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Dust grains are heated via this radiation and can transfer thermal energy during collisions with the gas.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] A measure of efficiency in the heating is given by the accommodation coefficient: $\alpha ={\frac {T_{2}-T}{T_{d}-T}}$ where *T* is the gas temperature, *Td* the dust temperature, and *T*2 the post-collision temperature of the gas atom or molecule.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This coefficient was measured by (Burke & Hollenbach 1983) as *α* = 0.35.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The process of fine structure cooling is dominant in most regions of the Interstellar Medium, except regions of hot gas and regions deep in molecular clouds.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] It occurs most efficiently with abundant atoms having fine structure levels close to the fundamental level such as: C II and O I in the neutral medium and O II, O III, N II, N III, Ne II and Ne III in H II regions.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Collisions will excite these atoms to higher levels, and they will eventually de-excite through photon emission, which will carry the energy out of the region.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] At lower temperatures, more levels than fine structure levels can be populated via collisions.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] will release a Ly-α photon upon de-excitation.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] is excited, it eventually returns to a lower energy state, emitting a photon which can leave the region, cooling the cloud.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Despite its extremely low density, photons generated in the ISM are prominent in nearly all bands of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In fact the optical band, on which astronomers relied until well into the 20th century, is the one in which the ISM is least obvious.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Radio waves are affected by the plasma properties of the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The lowest frequency radio waves, below ≈ 0.1 MHz, cannot propagate through the ISM since they are below its plasma frequency.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] At higher frequencies, the plasma has a significant refractive index, decreasing with increasing frequency, and also dependent on the density of free electrons.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Random variations in the electron density cause interstellar scintillation, which broadens the apparent size of distant radio sources seen through the ISM, with the broadening decreasing with frequency squared.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The variation of refractive index with frequency causes the arrival times of pulses from pulsars and Fast radio bursts to be delayed at lower frequencies (dispersion).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The amount of delay is proportional to the column density of free electrons (Dispersion measure, DM), which is useful for both mapping the distribution of ionized gas in the Galaxy and estimating distances to pulsars (more distant ones have larger DM).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] A second propagation effect is Faraday rotation, which affects linearly polarized radio waves, such as those produced by synchrotron radiation, one of the most common sources of radio emission in astrophysics.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Faraday rotation depends on both the electron density and the magnetic field strength, and so is used as a probe of the interstellar magnetic field.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The ISM is generally very transparent to radio waves, allowing unimpeded observations right through the disk of the Galaxy.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] There are a few exceptions to this rule.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The most intense spectral lines in the radio spectrum can become opaque, so that only the surface of the line-emitting cloud is visible.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This mainly affects the carbon monoxide lines at millimetre wavelengths that are used to trace molecular clouds, but the 21-cm line from neutral hydrogen can become opaque in the cold neutral medium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Such absorption only affects photons at the line frequencies: the clouds are otherwise transparent.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The other significant absorption process occurs in dense ionized regions.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These emit photons, including radio waves, via thermal bremsstrahlung.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] At short wavelengths, typically microwaves, these are quite transparent, but their brightness approaches the black body limit as $\propto \lambda ^{2.1}$ , and at wavelengths long enough that this limit is reached, they become opaque.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The frequency at which a particular nebula becomes optically thick depends on its *emission measure* $EM=\int n_{e}^{2}\,dl,$ the column density of squared electron number density.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The general transparency of the ISM to radio waves, especially microwaves, may seem surprising since radio waves at frequencies > 10 GHz are significantly attenuated by Earth's atmosphere (as seen in the figure).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] But the column density through the atmosphere is vastly larger than the column through the entire Galaxy, due to the extremely low density of the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The word 'interstellar' (between the stars) was coined by Francis Bacon in the context of the ancient theory of a literal sphere of fixed stars.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Later in the 17th century, when the idea that stars were scattered through infinite space became popular, it was debated whether that space was a true vacuum or filled with a hypothetical fluid, sometimes called *aether*, as in René Descartes' vortex theory of planetary motions.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In 1864, William Huggins used spectroscopy to determine that a nebula is made of gas.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Huggins had a private observatory with an 8-inch telescope, with a lens by Alvan Clark; but it was equipped for spectroscopy, which enabled breakthrough observations.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] From around 1889, Edward Barnard pioneered deep photography of the sky, finding many 'holes in the Milky Way'.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] At first he compared them to sunspots, but by 1899 was prepared to write: "One can scarcely conceive a vacancy with holes in it, unless there is nebulous matter covering these apparently vacant places in which holes might occur".
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These holes are now known as dark nebulae, dusty molecular clouds silhouetted against the background star field of the galaxy; the most prominent are listed in his Barnard Catalogue.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The first direct detection of cold diffuse matter in interstellar space came in 1904, when Johannes Hartmann observed the binary star Mintaka (Delta Orionis) with the Potsdam Great Refractor.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The stationary nature of the line led Hartmann to conclude that the gas responsible for the absorption was not present in the atmosphere of the star, but was instead located within an isolated cloud of matter residing somewhere along the line of sight to this star.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] This discovery launched the study of the interstellar medium.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Interstellar gas was further confirmed by Slipher in 1909, and then by 1912 interstellar dust was confirmed by Slipher.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Interstellar sodium was detected by Mary Lea Heger in 1919 through the observation of stationary absorption from the atom's "D" lines at 589.0 and 589.6 nanometres towards Delta Orionis and Beta Scorpii.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In the series of investigations, Viktor Ambartsumian introduced the now commonly accepted notion that interstellar matter occurs in the form of clouds.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Subsequent observations of the "H" and "K" lines of calcium by Beals (1936) revealed double and asymmetric profiles in the spectra of Epsilon and Zeta Orionis.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These were the first steps in the study of the very complex interstellar sightline towards Orion.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Asymmetric absorption line profiles are the result of the superposition of multiple absorption lines, each corresponding to the same atomic transition (for example the "K" line of calcium), but occurring in interstellar clouds with different radial velocities.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Because each cloud has a different velocity (either towards or away from the observer/Earth), the absorption lines occurring within each cloud are either blue-shifted or red-shifted (respectively) from the lines' rest wavelength through the Doppler Effect.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] These observations confirming that matter is not distributed homogeneously were the first evidence of multiple discrete clouds within the ISM.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The same year, Victor Hess's discovery of cosmic rays, highly energetic charged particles that rain onto the Earth from space, led others to speculate whether they also pervaded interstellar space.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] The following year, the Norwegian explorer and physicist Kristian Birkeland wrote: "It seems to be a natural consequence of our points of view to assume that the whole of space is filled with electrons and flying electric ions of all kinds.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] We have assumed that each stellar system in evolutions throws off electric corpuscles into space.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] It does not seem unreasonable therefore to think that the greater part of the material masses in the universe is found, not in the solar systems or nebulae, but in 'empty' space" (Birkeland 1913).
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Thorndike (1930) noted that "it could scarcely have been believed that the enormous gaps between the stars are completely void.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] Terrestrial aurorae are not improbably excited by charged particles emitted by the Sun.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In February 2014, NASA announced a greatly upgraded database for tracking polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) in the universe.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] According to scientists, more than 20% of the carbon in the universe may be associated with PAHs, possible starting materials for the formation of life.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] PAHs seem to have been formed shortly after the Big Bang, are widespread throughout the universe, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In April 2019, scientists, working with the Hubble Space Telescope, reported the confirmed detection of the large and complex ionized molecules of buckminsterfullerene (C60) (also known as "buckyballs") in the interstellar medium spaces between the stars.
[src:astrophysics/interstellar-medium] In September 2020, evidence was presented of solid-state water in the interstellar medium, and particularly, of water ice mixed with silicate grains in cosmic dust grains.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] A **neutron star** is the gravitationally collapsed core of a massive supergiant star.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] It results from the supernova explosion of a massive star—combined with gravitational collapse—that compresses the core past white dwarf star density to that of atomic nuclei.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Surpassed only by black holes, neutron stars are the second-smallest- and second-densest-known class of stellar objects.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Neutron stars have a radius on the order of 10 kilometers (6 miles) and a mass of about 1.4 solar masses (*M*☉).
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Stars that collapse into neutron stars typically have an initial total mass between 10 and 25 *M*☉ or possibly more for those that are especially rich in elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] There are thought to be around one billion neutron stars in the Milky Way, and at a minimum several hundred million, a figure obtained by estimating the number of stars that have undergone supernova explosions.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] However, many of them have existed for a long period of time and have cooled down considerably.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Originally it was thought that neutron stars would be difficult to detect due to low emissions.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] However, it was discovered that spinning stars emit radiation.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Most neutron stars that have been detected are pulsars or a part of a binary system.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Neutron stars in a binary system with a main sequence star can pull in large amounts of gas from its companion, a process called accretion.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] These binary systems continue to evolve, with many companions eventually becoming compact objects such as white dwarfs or neutron stars themselves, though other possibilities include a complete destruction of the companion through ablation or collision.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The study of neutron star systems is central to gravitational wave astronomy.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The merger of binary neutron stars produces gravitational waves and is associated with kilonovae and short gamma-ray bursts.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] In 2017, the LIGO and Virgo interferometer sites observed GW170817, the first direct detection of gravitational waves from such an event.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Prior to this, indirect evidence for gravitational waves was inferred by studying the gravity radiated from the orbital decay of a different type of (unmerged) binary neutron system, the Hulse–Taylor pulsar.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Any main-sequence star with an initial mass of greater than 8 *M*☉ (eight times the mass of the Sun) has the potential to become a neutron star.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] As the star evolves away from the main sequence, stellar nucleosynthesis produces an iron-rich core.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] When all nuclear fuel in the core has been exhausted, the core must be supported by degeneracy pressure alone.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Further deposits of mass from shell burning cause the core to exceed the Chandrasekhar limit.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Electron-degeneracy pressure is overcome, and the core collapses further, causing temperatures to rise to over 5×109 K.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] At these temperatures, photodisintegration (the breakdown of iron nuclei into alpha particles due to high-energy gamma rays) occurs.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] As the temperature of the core continues to rise, electrons and protons combine to form neutrons via electron capture, releasing a flood of neutrinos.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] When densities reach a nuclear density of 4×1017 kg/m3, a combination of strong force repulsion and neutron degeneracy pressure halts the contraction.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The contracting outer envelope of the star is halted and rapidly flung outwards by a flux of neutrinos produced in the creation of the neutrons, resulting in a supernova and leaving behind a neutron star.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] However, if the remnant has a mass greater than about 3 *M*☉, it instead becomes a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Observations of gravitational waves from neutron star merger GW170817, which is thought to have generated a black hole shortly afterward, have refined the mass limit estimate for a non-rotating neutron star to ~2.17 *M*☉.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] As the core of a massive star is compressed during a Type II supernova or a Type Ib or Type Ic supernova, and collapses into a neutron star, it retains most of its angular momentum.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Because it has only a tiny fraction of its parent's radius (sharply reducing its moment of inertia), a neutron star is formed with very high rotation speed and then, over a very long period, it slows.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Neutron stars are known that have rotation periods from about 1.4 ms to 30 s.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The neutron star's density also gives it very high surface gravity, with typical values ranging from 1012 to 1013 m/s2 (more than 1011 times that of Earth).
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] One measure of such immense gravity is the fact that neutron stars have an escape velocity of over half the speed of light.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The neutron star's gravity accelerates infalling matter to tremendous speed, and tidal forces near the surface can cause spaghettification.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Once formed, neutron stars no longer actively generate heat and cool over time, but they may still evolve further through collisions or accretion.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Most of the basic models for these objects imply that they are composed almost entirely of neutrons, as the extreme pressure causes the electrons and protons present in normal matter to combine into additional neutrons.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] These stars are partially supported against further collapse by neutron degeneracy pressure, just as white dwarfs are supported against collapse by electron degeneracy pressure.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] However, this is not by itself sufficient to hold up an object beyond 0.7 *M*☉ and repulsive nuclear forces increasingly contribute to supporting more massive neutron stars.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] If the remnant star has a mass exceeding the Tolman–Oppenheimer–Volkoff limit, approximately 2.2 to 2.9 *M*☉, the combination of degeneracy pressure and nuclear forces is insufficient to support the neutron star, causing it to collapse and form a black hole.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The most massive neutron star detected so far, PSR J0952–0607, is estimated to be 2.35±0.17 *M*☉.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Newly formed neutron stars may have surface temperatures of ten million kelvins or more.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] However, since neutron stars generate no new heat through fusion, they inexorably cool down after their formation.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Still, surface temperatures will be around one million kelvins after one thousand to one million years, and older, even cooler neutron stars are still easy to discover.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] For example, the well-studied neutron star, RX J1856.5−3754, has an average surface temperature of about 434,000 K.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] By comparison, the effective surface temperature of the Sun is only 5,780 K.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Neutron star material is remarkably dense: a normal-sized matchbox containing neutron-star material would have a weight of approximately 3 billion tonnes, the same weight as a 0.5-cubic-kilometer chunk of the Earth (a cube with edges of about 800 meters) from Earth's surface.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] As a star's core collapses, its rotation rate increases due to conservation of angular momentum, so newly formed neutron stars typically rotate at up to several hundred times per second.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] Some neutron stars emit beams of electromagnetic radiation that make them detectable as pulsars, and the discovery of pulsars by Jocelyn Bell Burnell and Antony Hewish in 1967 was the first observational suggestion that neutron stars exist.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The fastest-spinning neutron star known is PSR J1748−2446ad, rotating at a rate of 716 times per second or 42,960 revolutions per minute, giving a linear (tangential) speed at the surface on the order of 0.24‍*c* (i.e., nearly a quarter the speed of light).
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The equation of state of neutron stars is not currently known.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] This is because neutron stars are the second most dense known object in the universe, only less dense than black holes.
[src:astrophysics/neutron-star-p01] The extreme density means there is no way to replicate the material on Earth in laboratories, which is how equations of state for other things like ideal gases are tested.
